<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Conduct New Research into Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- British scientists are urgently
conducting fresh research into the safety of cow's milk amid
allegations that previous experiments held to show milk cannot be
infected with BSE are unreliable and inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
New tests, in which calves are being fed with milk from
BSE-infected cows, are under way at the Ministry of Agriculture's
laboratory, according to the Observer report today.
</P>
<P>
The experiment, the fifth into SBE and milk carried out by the
scientists since 1990, is intended to show whether calves are at
any greater risk of contracting BSE after prolonged feeding with
milk from their mothers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier experiments, on which the Ministry bases its claim
that milk is safe to drink, have been attacked as "worthless".
</P>
<P>
The Ministry says that there is no evidence BSE can be passed
on through milk and that the infective agent has not been found
even in milk from cows known to have the disease.
</P>
<P>
However, its assurances have been dismissed by some leading
scientists who say that the experiments were poor and
inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry said the new research had been going on for many
months. "Depending upon the outcome, further research may be
necessary, but if the findings are negative we believe that it
would give a further assurance over the safety of milk. We remain
of the view that milk is completely safe." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
