<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Emerges Mighty Giant in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- With the title-winning rank
unprecedently expanded, the long-time European domains being
encroached upon, Asia, the world's most populous continent has
emerged as a mighty giant in world sports.
</P>
<P>
Nine Asian countries and regions stroke gold in Atlanta, four
more than at the Barcelona Games, six more than in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Over half a century leading to the Los Angeles Olympics, Asia
had ramained a sports dwarf, totalling just 110 golds since Japan
and India produced Asia's first gold medalists in the 1928
Helsinki Games.
</P>
<P>
Asia, with the fastest growing economy in the world, has beefed
up its sports with big money and high technologies, and it has all
paid off.
</P>
<P>
In the recent four Olympics, Asia has garnered 124 gold medals,
more than the total it had registered in the previous 14 Games.
</P>
<P>
Born agile and flexible, the Asians swept all four golds in
table tennis, three in diving, four in badminton and six in judo
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Among the Asian haul of 34 gold, -- silver and -- bronze medals#,
these three in athletics weigh heaviest -- Chinese Wang Junxia's
5,000 gold plus her 10,000 silver and Syrian Ghada Shouaa's
history-making gold at heptathlon.
</P>
<P>
Wang, hailed as "Oriental Mystery Deer", beat the runner-up by
more than 40 meters in the 5,000 meters final to lift the Asian
women's first Olympic distance running gold.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Chinese, the only runner entered for both the
5,000 and 10,000 meters here, picked up the silver in the longer
distance of 10,000 meters race, Asia's first ever medal for the
event.
</P>
<P>
Shouaa broke the American and European domination of the
heptathlon, winning the first-ever Olympic gold for Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria wasn't the only Asian country or region to end its Olympic
gold drought in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong got the first taste of Olympic gold medal since it
made the first appearance in the 1952 Olympics, as Lee Lai Shan
triumped at the women's boards sailing.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, making an Olympic debut as an independent nation,
landed two golds here -- one from Aleksandr Parygin in modren
pentathlon and the other from Yuriy Melnichenko at Greco-Roman
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
China, South Korea and Japan remained vanguards for Asia,
taking 16, eight and three golds respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese kept their dominance in table tennis and diving and
shone in shooting and weightlifting.
</P>
<P>
World top women's table tennis player Deng Yaping, whose
aggressive game held all opponents in awe, repeated her
singles-doubles glory to become the only woman to successfully
defend two titles in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Fu Mingxia, who became the youngest Olympic champion at age of 14
in Barcelona, hit a gold double in the women's platform and
springboard diving events.
</P>
<P>
South Korea underlined its prowess in archery, badminton and
judo by winning two golds from each event.
</P>
<P>
Archer Kim Kyung-Wook turned out a heroine for South Korea. She
scored six 10s en route to winning the highly-pressured 12-arrow
women's final and then anchored the South Korean side to the top
podium of the team event.
</P>
<P>
Japan, dethroned by China as Asia's No. 1 sports power in the 1984
Los Angeles Games, showed its depth in judo with three gold
medals t their credit in the Atlanta Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
