<HEADLINE> Aidid's Son Succeeds Late Somali General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Leadership Council of the
late Somali General Mohammed Farrah Aidid today elected his son
Hussein Mohamed Aidid as "president".
</P>
<P>
According to South Mogadishu Radio which supports the late
Aidid, the council and the cabinet unanimously elected Hussein
Mohamed Aidid as the "President of Somalia" under the
transitional charters article 16 paragraph 4.
</P>
<P>
The nomination followed a series of meetings by the two
administrational bodies of the late Aidid's government at the
request of the United Somali Congress of Somali National Alliance
(USC/SNA).
</P>
<P>
The radio declared that the new president will have all powers
according to the charter as the chairman of the Leadership
Council and of the Ministerial Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The radio did not say when and where the new president will be
sworn in, nor was the voice of Hussein Mohamed Aidid heard
on the radio.
</P>
<P>
But there has been wide speculation that he may give his first
speech tonight.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believe Hussein will be working under the
guidance of his late father's political advisors. This may make
him "a paper tiger".
</P>
<P>
Supporters of Ali Mahdi Mohamed have described the move as an
unfortunate act. "We thought the death of General Aidid will
bring about peace in Somalia, but the nomination of his son is
now further complicating any possible solution of Somalia's long
standing political crises," said Mudey Ahmed Adde, a Somali
political analyst. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
