<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Minnows Bang Upon Centennial Olympic Doors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Since the gates to the Centennial
Olympic Games swung open for all 197 IOC members here two weeks
ago, minnows in sports have been making history with their
national anthems echoing over this southeastern American city.
</P>
<P>
Greece, cradle of the modern Olympics, ended its 100-year
Olympic medal drought in gymnastics when Ioannis Melissanidis
stepped onto the victory podium as the winner of the men's floor
routine.
</P>
<P>
Despite complaints about biased scoring by judges, Melissanidis
has gone down in history as the first Greek gymnast to be crowned
since the first modern games in 1896 when Ioannis Mitropoulos won
the rings on home soil.
</P>
<P>
Ghada Shouaa augured a new sport era for Syria as she became
the first Olympic champion in her country. She received a personal
telegram of greetings from the Syrian president after her victory
in the women's heptathlon on July 29.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 24, Shouaa, a former cager, came out from nowhere
to beat a star-studded field, putting herself into the spotlight
as the most outstanding female athlete in track and field both in
the world championships and in the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Fatuma Roba, a policewoman from Ethiopia, is the first
African to win the Olympic women's marathon, an event adopted at
the Olympics in 1984.
</P>
<P>
She cruised to her victory with the largest margin of two
minutes in the Olympic marathon history.
</P>
<P>
From the Centennial Games, the Ecuadoreans back home danced in
the streets after Jefferson Perez won the men's 20-kilometer walk.
No Ecuadorean athlete had won any Olympic medal, let alone the
coveted gold.
</P>
<P>
President Sixto Duran-Ballen declared Perez a "national hero"
and a commemorative stamp bearing Perez's image is reported to be
issued soon.
</P>
<P>
The first ever gold medal was also won by Claudia Poll for
Costa Rica in the women's 200-meter freestyle, who beat
top-favored German Franziska van Almsick to second place, and by
Venuste Niyongabo for Burundi in the men's 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
For Hong Kong, windsurfer Lee Lai Shan became the first Olympic
champion in 44 years when she clinched the gold medal in the
women's Mistral class sailing on July 28.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia also strode into the gold tally for the first time
when their men shuttlers Rexy Mainaky and Ricky Subagja triumphed
in the men's badminton doubles.
</P>
<P>
Bahamas, Moldova and Mozambique also had their colors hoisted
for the first time in the Olympic competition venues, a
justification that any athlete, regardless of race, sex or age,
could achieve his or her best under the Olympic motto of being
faster, higher and stronger.
</P>
<P>
Other minor sports nations who have won either silver or bronze
medals at the current Games include Namibia, Trinidad and Tobago,
Puerto Rico, Mongolia, Uganda, India, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Thailand, Israel and Moldova.
</P>
<P>
As an individual, Irish woman swimmer Michelle Smith became the
talk of the Games after she emerged as the sole Olympian with
three gold medals from individual events -- the 100- and 200-meter
individual medlays and the 400-meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
While suspicions fanned by the envious hosts about her drug
taking were making the round, the Irish swimmer dismissed them
with an open mind and went home the victor as all her urine tests
were cleared by the Medical Commission of the International
Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
With the Games curtains to close in a few hours, sports fans
and authorities remain confident that more minnows will make their
mark on the Olympic boulevard sooner or later.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
