<HEADLINE> Germany Dominates Canoe-Kayak Sprint Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany took one more gold to
extend their medal credit advantage in Olympic canoe-kayak sprint
competitions which ended here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This gold from the men's K2 500-meter event rounded off
Germany's gold medal haul of 19 at the current Centennial Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
The German pair, Kay Bluhm and Torsten Gutsche, were clocked in
1:28.697, ahead of Italy and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Germany tops the sprint medal tally with four gold and two
silver medals, followed by Italy with two golds, two silvers and
one bronze.
</P>
<P>
Antonio Rossi of Italy, who took a gold for his country with
Daniele Scarpa in the K2 event Saturday, won the first event today
in the men's K1 500m event.
</P>
<P>
"It's beautiful to win with another person. Today there is the
satisfaction to be the only one and have the honor," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was a big day for Hungary as they collected two more gold
medals, in the women's K1 500m and in the men's C2 500m.
</P>
<P>
Moldova became the surprising runners-up in the men's C2 500m,
the only medal in the sprint for the tiny country.
</P>
<P>
Victor Reneischi said after the final:"I did not expect to win
a medal in this event." He said the good result was due to "many
years of training and experience."
</P>
<P>
"When we had chance, we used it all."
</P>
<P>
The men's C500m title went to Czech Republic while Sweden
claimed the women's K2 500m crown Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
