<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Could Destroy Remaining Tropical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of Earth's
remaining 2 billion hectares of tropical forests could be lost to
agriculture, says a new report by the Consultative Group on
International Agricultural Research (CGIAR).
</P>
<P>
The annual rate of tropical forest loss is not diminishing,
despite rising global awareness and efforts, the report says.
Some 29 hectares of tropical forest are lost every minute, or 15.4
million ha per year.
</P>
<P>
"There is no magic bullet to saving the world's tropical
forests," says Ismail Serageldin, the CGIAR chairman and World
Bank Vice President, "What is needed is a comprehensive effort to
attack the root causes of deforestation -- poverty, rising
population, bad natural resource management and distorted forest
policy."
</P>
<P>
The report says the main threat to tropical forests comes from
poor farmers who have no other option to feeding their families
other than slashing and burning a patch of forest and growing food
crops. Slash-and-burn agriculture results in the loss of 10
million ha of land per year.
</P>
<P>
According to data from CGIAR research institutes, some 350
million people in tropical countries are forest dwellers who
derive half or more of their income from the forest. Forest
provide directly 10 percent of the employment in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
CGIAR is the would's largest international consortium for
agricultural research and is jointly sponsored by the World Bank,
the United Nations Development Programme, the Food and Agriculture
organization and the United Nations Environment Programme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
