<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stranded Israelis Leave Cyprus for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Forty-seven Israelis, stranded
at Cyprus' Larnaca International Airport following a bomb threat
aboard a Polish airliner, left this afternoon for home on board
two small private planes.
</P>
<P>
According to the Cyprus News Agency, the Israelis were on a
"Lot" flight from the Polish capital of Warsaw to Tel Aviv,
Israel, when the Boeing 737 was forced to make an emergency
landing at Larnaca early this morning, following an anonymous
telephone call saying that there was a bomb on the plane.
</P>
<P>
All 89 passengers on board the Boeing 737 disembarked to allow
the Cypriot authorities to carry out a thorough search.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the airport said that nothing suspicious was found
and the Boeing took off from Larnaca five hours later.
</P>
<P>
The 47 Israelis refused to continue their journey aboard the
Lot aircraft even after the security check and alternative
arrangements were made especially for their departure, the Cyprus
News Agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
