<HEADLINE> Egypt Arrests Two Extremists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's security authorities have
arrested two extremists in the latest crackdown on suspected
Moslem fundamentalist militants.
</P>
<P>
An official source at the Interior Ministry was quoted by the
Egyptian Middle East News Agency as saying today that the two
extremists, identified as Ahmed Mahmoud Mohamed al Khouly, 31, and
Hani Mohamed Mansour, 19, belong to the military wing of Al-Gamaa
al-Islamiya (the Islamic Group), Egypt's largest Moslem militant
group.
</P>
<P>
The group has been blamed for much of the violence against the
government since 1992, when Moslem militants launched a violent
campaign in an attempt to overthrow the secular government and
replace it with strict Islamic rule in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
It claimed responsibility for a bloody attack in Cairo on April
18, in which 18 Greek tourists were killed.
</P>
<P>
The security authorities have fiercely cracked down on
militants and succeeded in containing their activities. Recently
there have been only sporadic attacks by Moslem militants in
villages in southern Egypt, mainly on policemen and Christians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
