<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-04 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Official Condemns Hamas Leaders Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) official today sharply condemned leaders of
Hamas, the Islamic Resistance Movement, accusing them of creating
tensions in the Palestinian autonomous areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Amin Al-Hindi, head of the Palestinian
general intelligence service, as saying that Hamas leadership
abroad had sent instructions to the organization's activists to
oppose the PNA rule.
</P>
<P>
Al-Hindi said that he had intercepted messages from abroad,
which instruct people in the West Bank and Gaza Strip to stage
riots and take actions against the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Al-Hindi's remarks came after Friday's violent confrontation in
the West Bank town of Tulkarm between Palestinian police and Hamas
demonstrators, who demanded the release of Hamas prisoners.
</P>
<P>
One man was killed and 15 others injured during the riot when
Palestinian police guarding the Tulkarm jail clashed with
stone-throwing protesters who stormed the prison for a short
period of time.
</P>
<P>
Hamas said Ibrahim Hadayeh was killed by the Palestinian
police during a "peaceful" demonstration, while Palestinian Radio
shifted responsibility for Hadayeh's death, saying he was shot
dead by armed Hamas activists.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere in the Palestinian streets was very tense after
the death Wednesday night of Mahmoud Jumayal, a Fatah activist,
who was tortured to death in a Palestinian jail.
</P>
<P>
Hamas issued a statement Saturday, calling PNA President
Yasser Arafat "a collaborator," and called for an "intifada"
(uprising) against the PNA and Israel.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to ease the tensions in the West Bank,
Palestinian police, under the order of Arafat, today released 15
Hamas detainees in Tulkarm, who did not flee from the prison
during the riot Friday.
</P>
<P>
Another four prisoners were also freed on health reasons, as
well as several others who are relatives of Hadayeh, while 50
detainees who tried to escape Friday were caught and sent back to
their cells in the prison.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian police arrested another 200 people
involved in Friday's disturbance, the first of its kind since the
Palestinian self-rule started three years ago.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Israeli army commanders in the West
Bank have been ordered to beef up their troops, but not to
interfere in the troubles among the Palestinians, according to the
Israel Radio report.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli troops were also instructed to help the Palestinian
police to treat the wounded people, but to let the Palestinian
police themselves deal with any violent demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
The army had already declared Nablus and Tulkarm as closed
military zones immediately after the violence broke out, barring
Israelis from entering the two West Bank towns.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, residents in Tulkarm said that the Palestinian
police imposed a curfew on the town briefly Friday, the first time
the PNA has ever done on a Palestinian town.
</P>
<P>
Israel had handed over Nablus and Tulkarm, as well as Jenin,
Kalkilya, Ramallah and Bethlehem in the West Bank to the PNA by
the end of last year, in accordance with the Oslo peace accords.
</P>
<P>
A senior Israeli security source told Israel Radio that Israel
was willing to see stability in the Palestinian autonomous areas
and the continuation of the rule of PNA President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
</TEXT>
