<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sanctions Against Iran, Libya to Harm Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton is
expected to sign Monday a congressional act aimed at toughening
sanctions against Iran and Libya, two countries accused by
Washington of supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The act, often called d'Amato Act in reference to its main
advocate Republican Senator Alfonso d'Amato, authorizes U.S. to
punish any foreign oil company that invests more than 40 million
U.S. dollars in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This act, passed in the name of fighting terrorism, will
inevitably worsen the tension between Washington and its European
allies, who have great investments in oil industry of the two
Middle East countries with 20 percent of their oil consumptions
coming from them.
</P>
<P>
When Clinton signed the Helms-Burton Act authorizing
extra-territorial sanctions against foreign businesses having
commercial ties with Cuba, he met strong opposition from European
countries and was forced to suspend some of the articles of the
law on sueing foreign companies buying or selling Cuban assets
that used to belong to U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
This time, the d'Amato Act authorizes the same function of
extraterritoriality extending a U.S. law to international trade,
which will no doubt arouse strong protest and even lead to
reprisals by European countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-European split over the issue was shown at the Group
of Seven most industrialized nations ministerial conference on
terrorism held last week in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The final declaration of the conference and the 25 measures it
adopted to combat terrorism did not mention international
sanctions against Iran, Iraq, Libya and Sudan, the four countries
finger-pointed by Washington for supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The French government has made it clear that it will not
support any action mixing the fight against terrorism with
international trade, and has indicated that it will maintain a
dialogue with Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States intensified its campaign against
Iran in the past week, hinting that it was behind the bomb attack
on an American base in Dahran, Saudi Arabia in late June.
</P>
<P>
Agence France Presse (AFP) said that Teheran is more and more
in the "collimator" of Washington, but added that the Europeans
know that this new act is closely linked with the present
presidential election in the U.S., with Clinton and Republican
presidential candidate Bob Dole contesting each other over the
issue of fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said at the beginning of the year that he was totally
opposed to extraterritorial measures in imposing sanctions.
However, the attack on U.S. base in Saudi Arabia and the
mysterious explosion of the TWA Boeing 747 on July 17 above New
York have changed the political context, said AFP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0045 </DOCNO>
