<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Calls on Arabs to Normalize Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today called on Arab leaders to realize
normalization of relations with Israel, saying peace with what he
termed as "undemocratic countries" only started with their
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks when talking at an Israeli Bonds
meeting today about the country's relations with its Arab
neighbors, including Egypt, Jordan, Syria and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted the prime minister as claiming that he did
not expect the "democratization" of the Middle East in the
foreseeable future, "therefore the security aspect has to be
insisted upon."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he demanded the Arab leaders make a "conscious
decision" to normalize ties with Israel, saying peace "must come
from atop."
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of seeking both peace and
normalization, praising Jordan's "clear commitment" in this
aspect. Netanyahu will go to Jordan Monday on his first official
visit to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Although Israel and Egypt have yet to further normalize their
relations, Netanyahu said, he was confident about the future as he
received a clear commitment from President Hosni Mubarak when he
visited Cairo two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to make peace with Israel, but
the pace of normalization of relations has been relatively slow
due to differences over the peace process and other bilateral
issues.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli-Palestinian ties, Netanyahu said he intended to do
the same. However, he pledged to insist on the security issue in
dealing with the Palestinians to prevent the repetition of
"terrorist attacks."
</P>
<P>
He urged PNA leader Yasser Arafat to explain to the
Palestinian people that "the idea of war with Israel is over,"
and that Israel and Palestinians should make peace.
</P>
<P>
On Israeli-Syrian peace talks, Netanyahu said Israel must
insist on both peace and security. He added that despite all the
differences, the two sides could hold negotiations on all
concerns without imposing views on each other.
</P>
<P>
Finally, he expressed the hope that "peace with security"
would be reached, and that "normalization would be down the
line."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Arab peace process has been fully stalled since
the May 29 Israeli elections, despite repeated calls from Arab
countries for immediate resumption of the process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, the hardline Likud leader, has adopted a tougher
line toward the peace process by rejecting the land-for-peace
principle. He also erected three so-called pillars in future
peace process: security, reciprocity and democratization of Arab
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
