<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Warns World of US Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
warned the international community of the latest U.S. military
threats to Iran.
</P>
<P>
This came when Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati
submitted a letter to U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali
via Iran's permanent representative to the U.N. Kamal Kharrazi.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister cautioned against what he called
"threatening behavior by the American government" toward Iran,
according to the official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Velayati urged the U.N. chief to take all necessary measures
to prevent the dangerous consequences caused by the
U.S. irresponsible acts for the world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, he conveyed the deep concern of the Iranian
government about the continued hostile remarks of officials of
the United States and it's policies vis-a-vis the Islamic
Republic in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the "alarming and threatening" dimensions of the
statements made by U.S. Secretary of Defense William Perry, he
called the statements as blatant examples of political
manipulation of public opinion already apprehensive about the
recent tragic events.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry said in an interview with
National Public Radio Friday that Iran was "possibly" behind the
June 25 bombing that killed 19 U.S. servicemen at Dhahran in
eastern Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
However, Velayati dismissed the allegations as an affront to
the sovereignty of his country.
</P>
<P>
Perry's warning that those responsible would have to pay a
heavy price was widely interpreted in the U.S. media as an
indiction that the United States could launch a military strike
against Iran.
</P>
<P>
He termed U.S. threats of use of force against Iran as an
"arrogant and callous disregard" for the most basic principle of
the rules of international law and the charter of the United
Nations and a clear example of "state terrorism."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized Iran believes that the U.S. government may be
seeking an excuse to embark on adventurism against and
confrontation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister reminded the U.N. secretary-general that
prevention of such potentially dangerous consequences is the
primary responsibility of the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
