<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-04 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Curb Labor Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 4 (Xinhua)-- Kuwait will implement new
measures in curbing manpower traffic as well as protecting
expatriate laborers' rights in the country, which attracts most of
its manpower from other countries.
</P>
<P>
A decision issued Saturday by Kuwaiti Social Affairs and Labor
Minister Ahmad Al-Klaib indicated that the Kuwaiti authorities
would allow the establishment of private labor agencies for the
recruitment of foreign manpower from outside and inside Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
A set of regulations for organizing the functioning of the
recruitment agencies will come into effect after two months.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulations, the agencies will act as mediators
between laborers and employers in accordance with official
binding contracts.
</P>
<P>
The agencies and employers should sign contracts which should
include the number of employees wanted, their qualifications and
experience.
</P>
<P>
The amount of charges to be paid by the employers, wages of
laborers and the period during which the agencies will provide
the required employees would also be specified.
</P>
<P>
The decision said that agencies are totally banned from taking
any direct or indirect charges from laborers and those found to
be charging laborers for either recruitment or maintaining their
jobs will risk closure and withdrawal of commercial license.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly 1.2 million foreign nationals in Kuwait, most
of them laborers from about 130 countries, accounting for 83
percent of the Kuwaiti labor market, according to statistics by
the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, labor traffic has been rampant in the country
and labor Mafia brought foreign laborers into the country
charging hundreds, even 1,000 Kuwait dinars (3,300 U.S. dollars)
per head just for a visa.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulations, Those who open a recruitment
agency must submit a bank guarantee worth 30,000 Kuwait dinars
(99,000 dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
