<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-04 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Premier on Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Karim Kabariti said here today that Jordan's national economic and
social reform has produced real growth in the gross national
product (GNP) by nearly 7 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti said in his address to a session of the Lower House of
Parliament that the reform, which started in 1989 with the help of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), also reduced the budget
deficit to 4 percent in the GNP compared with 24 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
He said the success of the reform has also helped Jordan
rebuild its foreign currency reserve and maintain the stability of
the exchange rate of dinar.
</P>
<P>
It has also reduced the inflation rate to 4 percent this year
from 26 percent in 1989, and the foreign debt to less than 100
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) from 200 percent in
1989.
</P>
<P>
The House session today was devoted to discussion of
reallocation of wheat subsidies so that only the citizens who
deserve the subsidies would be entitled to it.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said ever since the government adopted
national restructuring program, it has been eager to maintain the
stability in the general level of prices so as to maintain the
standard of living at acceptable levels.
</P>
<P>
The government, said Kabariti, has done so by subsidizing
basic commodities despite the fact that the prices on world market
have risen.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the rise in the international prices and the
accompanying increases in quantities consumed have in turn
produced the increase in the amount of subsidy, which reached some
180 million dinars (252 million U.S. dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the amount of subsidy allocated in the general
budget this year totaled 38 million dinars (53.2 million dollars)
only.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti said the government decided to change the form of
subsidy "from indirect to direct" cash subsidy to ensure that
those who deserve the subsidy are benefiting from it.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has failed so far to convince the
public that the "rechanneling" rather than "lifting" of the
bread subsidies will not further reduce their standard of living.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties, interests groups and various
professional unions strongly oppose the government's plan of
lifting the subsidies on wheat while compensating the citizens
with 15 dinars (21 dollars) per capita a year.
</P>
<P>
Forty-one lawmakers out of the 80-member of the Lower House
even threatened to seek a no-confidence vote in the government if
the government goes ahead with the plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is expected to carry out the plan in
the face of the strong protests.
</P>
<P>
"I am exercising my powers as prime minister under the
Constitution and the parliament has the right to exercise its
rights by voting confidence in the government if the deputies are
not convinced by the government's views," said Kabariti.
</P>
<P>
The government had planned to announce the decision last
Wednesday but postponed until after today's session of the Lower
House in a bid to avoid direct confrontation with the deputies.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to announce the decision in a few
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
