<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serb Leader Promises to Do Utmost for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A Bosnian Serb leader said today
the Serb authorities were doing their utmost to ensure that the
first post-war elections would be held as planned and most
people, especially refugees, would be included in the voting.
</P>
<P>
The Serb parliament speaker Momclo Krajisnik made the remarks
in a statement to the local radio station in the central Serbian
town of Kragujevac.
</P>
<P>
He complained that Muslims and Serbs were not in the same
position because the vote would be taking place in embassies of
the Muslim-Croat federation in those countries that have sheltered
Bosnian refugees.
</P>
<P>
"Regardless of this, everything has been done for elections to
take place, primarily because the Dayton accords envisage that
sanctions against Yugoslavia will be lifted 10 days after the
elections take place," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million Bosnian people have become refugees and
displaced persons. All the refugees above 18 years of age have
rights to cast ballots during the elections. They can vote in the
current country they are staying now or they can go back to Bosnia
to vote.
</P>
<P>
"We do not fear the elections because our people have opted to
preserve Republika Srpska. The only thing with which the
international community is blackmailing us is the issue of Brcko,
where elections are trying to be postponed in a way, although
there is no justification for this, nor can we agree to it,"
Krajisnik said.
</P>
<P>
Both Serbs and Muslims claim sovereignty over Brcko, a
controversial town in northeastern Bosnia. Under the Dayton
accords, only a special arbitration commission will determine the
line of separation in the wider area of this town located on the
bottleneck of the corridor linking eastern and western parts of
Republika Srpska. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
