<HEADLINE> Iraq, China Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and China signed a protocol
on economic and trade cooperation, which provides for expansion of
cooperation in the economic, trade and scientific fields.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was signed by Shi Weisan, Director General of the
West Asia and Africa Department in the Chinese Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Ministry and Hatem Mara'i, undersecretary of
the Iraqi Ministry of Trade.
</P>
<P>
The protocol shows the desire of the Chinese enterprises to
offer foodstuffs and medicines to Iraq under the U.N.-Iraqi
oil-for-food formula signed in May.
</P>
<P>
It also ensures the development of cooperation between the two
countries in areas such as health, transportation, communication
and agriculture as well as exchange of expertise.
</P>
<P>
It also revives the Sino-Iraqi ministerial committee for trade,
economic and scientific cooperation, which is expected to convene
its ninth session in China late this year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
Shi said the protocol would open new horizons for the
development of the bilateral trade relations, according to the
Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The 17-member Chinese trade delegation led by Shi Weisan
arrived here on July 28 and left today for home after a one-week
visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It is the largest Chinese trade delegation to visit Iraq since
the signing of the U.N.-Iraqi deal which allows Iraq to sell 2
billion U.S. dollars of oil in a period of six months to buy food
and other supplies for its people hard hit by the six-year-old
U.N. sanctions against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
