<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say They've Found Earlist Sexual Differentiation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese biologists have found
indications from organic material that sexual differentiation
occurred as early as 620 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yun, a professor of biology at Beijing University
revealed the news today to participants at the 30th International
Geological Congress in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Some biologists say they believe this is the only reliable
evidence so far of sexual reproduction of multicellular organisms
in the Precambrian period.
</P>
<P>
The matter indicates that a distinction between sexes and
sexual reproduction may have been the direct cause of the
occurrence of animal and plant species some 570 million years ago
during the Cambrian period.
</P>
<P>
In southwest China's Guizhou Province, Prof. Zhang found
fossils of multicellular plants with signs of sexual
differentiation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang explained that, for a long period of more than one
billion years before the Precambrian, the highest form of life on
earth consisted of only one cell that had no sexual
differentiation, something like chlorella or an amoeba in modern
times.
</P>
<P>
That sexual differentiation made the reproduction of living
things more complex and increased their genetic information, so
that it provided the potential of biological evolution.
</P>
<P>
"After sexual differentiation appeared, the pace of biological
evolution accelerated," he said, and "men and women appeared, and
then love and ensuing outstanding cultures."
</P>
<P>
But from the point of view of biology, sexual distinctions and
other phenomena related to sex are simply resultant from
biological evolution, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
