<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funeral for Former French PM Michel Debre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The funeral of former French prime
minister, Michel Debre, one of the founders of the Fifth Republic,
was held today in Amboise, Indre-et-Loire. He died last Thursday
aged of 84.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 people, including President Jacques Chirac,
attended the funeral in small Roman church. It was presided by the
Archbishop of Tours, Jean Honore.
</P>
<P>
Michel Debre's grandson gave a testimony in memory of his
grandfather who, he said, had always wanted France to be "strong
and tolerant, conquering and democratic, loyal and republican."
</P>
<P>
The flags of former Resistance fighters against the Nazis were
paraded by a guard of honor ahead of the cortege, and the coffin
was draped with the French tricolour, a sword of the French
Academy of which he was a member, and a tie of Commander of the
Legion of Honors.
</P>
<P>
Debre joined the Resistance against Germany during World War II
and was representative of General Charles de Gaulle when France
was liberated from the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
He participated in writing the Constitution of the Fifth
Republic which has ruled the country since 1958, and was prime
minister under President de Gaulle from 1959 to 1962. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
