<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding Reported on China's Major Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The water level of the Yangtze
river is rising, while some parts of Yellow and Huaihe rivers are
already at flood stage, the State Flood-Control and Drought-Relief
Headquarters reported today.
</P>
<P>
Following a gradual drop, the level of the Yangtze River in the
middle and lower reaches has risen again since August 1 because of
typhoon and subsequent torrential rains in east China's coastal
areas.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Cheng Jiling, a hydrometric station on
Dongting Lake in the river's middle reaches, is 1.2 to 1.67 meters
higher than the danger level.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the excessive amount of rainfall, the trunk
streams of the Yellow River are also flooding, with a total volume
of 7,600 cubic meters passing through the Huayuankou Hydrometric
Station at 14 hours today, the biggest since 1985. The water
level of the station reached 94.73 meters, 0.4 meter higher than
the record level of 1992.
</P>
<P>
Some tributaries of the Huaihe river have also reported the
biggest flooding since 1963, also because of rainstorms.
</P>
<P>
Government organizations, engineering task forces and military
forces along these rivers are actively involved in the anti-flood
and relief work during the major flooding period, usually from
early July to late August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
