<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worst Drought in 50 Years Hits Lower Normandy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The worst drought in 50 years in
France has hit the region of Lower Normandy, seriously affecting
the traditional cattle rearing industry in an area known for its
green fields.
</P>
<P>
Water consumption in three areas of Normandy is rationed, the
result of little rainfall since October last year. The area of
Calvados has had less than 7.1 millimeters of rain in July, says
the local press.
</P>
<P>
One of the worst hit areas of Normandy is in the west where
there is no grass and cattle have been fed winter supplies of
silage.
</P>
<P>
"I have never used winter stocks to feed my 60 milk cows in
summer as I am doing now...This hurts my heart really badly and we
are going to buy grass stocks even though we are rationing the
cows' food and we don't have much money." said Jacques Hedouin, a
43-year-old cattle breeder at Gouville-sur-Mer.
</P>
<P>
"The drought adds to the mad cow crisis. This is a real
catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
He said he was going to sell some of his cows at 9-13 francs a
kilogram and expected a 100,000 franc loss.
</P>
<P>
The vegetable growers of Lower Normandy are as worried as
cattle breeders. Things were made more difficult after a local
government in Lingerville banned the use of irrigation from 13:00
to 17:00 hours, the hottest of the day.
</P>
<P>
"I can use my electrical irrigation system which does not
bother my neighbors at night as diesel pumps do. But the watering
is not enough and 30 percent of the vegetables are unsellable,"
said Daniel Mahe, a local farmer.
</P>
<P>
According to official forecasters, the mean rainfall rate in
Lower Normandy was expected to be 50 percent down this year, and
it could be 85 percent down in worst-hit areas like Calvados and
Deauville. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
