<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Demanded for Former South Korean President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean prosecutor today
demanded the death penalty and a 278 million U.S. dollar fine for
former President Chun Doo-hwan charged with mutiny, treason and
bribery.
</P>
<P>
In the 27th trial session held at the Seoul District Court for
Chun, another former president, Roh Tae-woo, and their followers
for their roles in the military revolt on December 12, 1979 and
the brutal suppression of the uprising on May 18, 1980, senior
public prosecutor Kim Sang-hee also demanded that Roh be sentenced
to life in prison and fined 355 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Life in prison was also asked for former First Army Corps
commander, Hwang Young-si, and former Special Warfare Forces
commander, Chung Ho-yong. Fifteen year prison terms were sought
for eight other defendants including former defense minister, Choo
Young-bock.
</P>
<P>
It was demanded that a former commander of the 30th Security
Group, Chang Se-dong, receive 12 years in prison, while a 10-year
prison term was sought for three other former officers including a
commander of the Army's 20th Division, Park Jun-byung.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the court, the prosecution asked the bench to hand
down severe punishment to the defendants as provided by law.
</P>
<P>
The 16 former South Korean officers including Chun and Roh have
been indicted for mutiny or treason, or both. The mutiny and
treason charges stem from their roles in the 1979 military revolt
and the 1980 suppression of the uprising in Kwangju, capital of
South Korea's South Cholla Province.
</P>
<P>
Chun seized power on August 27, 1980, and ruled the nation
until February 1988. He was followed by Roh who stepped down in
February 1993.
</P>
<P>
The two former presidents, who were arrested last year, have
also been indicted for graft. They allegedly received huge illegal
funds from businessmen while in office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
