<HEADLINE> State To Combat Epidemics In Flood-Stricken Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- State Councillor Peng Peiyun
today urged government officials in flood-affected areas in China
to concentrate on preventing and controlling the outbreak of
epidemic diseases while trying to hold losses from the disaster to
a minimum.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national telephone conference on disaster relief
and epidemic control, Peng said all relevant government
organizations and the Red Cross should provide prompt
transportation of aid, medicines, medical apparatuses and
instruments, and other necessities to disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
The public should be provided with more knowledge about
sanitation to protect themselves from diseases, she said.
</P>
<P>
Since the summer set in, central China's Hunan, Hubei, east
China's Jiangxi, Anhui and Zhejiang provinces, and Guangxi and
Guizhou provinces in the south and southwest have been seriously
affected by flooding.
</P>
<P>
But the epidemic situation as of June was not bad, with rate of
incidence and mortality from 25 epidemic diseases across China
having dropped by 6.07 percent and 6.66 percent respectively from
the same period last year, and the incidence of gastro-intestinal
diseases rising in some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Government at all levels should improve the basic health care
system and pay close attention to epidemic disease control, the
conference was told, and special aid should be provided by the
central government disaster-relief fund for prevention and
treatment of epidemic diseases.
</P>
<P>
Monitoring of the disinfecting of drinking water and protection
of food should be beefed up, while measures should be taken to
protect people in flood-stricken areas from the danger of
ingesting pesticides, industrial salts, and polluted foods by
mistake, the conference was told. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
