<HEADLINE> Mugabe Launches Polio Immunisation Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe today
launched the Zimbabwe national immunisation days (NIDS) by giving
several children the oral polio vaccine at a ceremony here.
</P>
<P>
This was part of a worldwide campaign to eradicate polio from
the planet by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch, Mugabe said the NIDS were an important
event in the fight against preventable diseases through
vaccination and toward the ultimate eradication of poliomyelitis
in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
''May i take this opportunity to urge all parents and
guardians to present and have all their children vaccinated
against polio, taking advantage of the vaccination centers during
the national immunisation days, whether or not the child has
previously been immunised against poliomyelitis,'' said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He said since independence the Zimbabwean government had made
great strides in the provision of basic health to children.
</P>
<P>
He said the expanded program on immunisation was one of the
primary health care programs that had tremendous impact in
reducing infant and child mortality and morbidity from serious
childhood diseases which could be prevented by immunisation.
</P>
<P>
He said according to the 1992 census, infant mortality had
been reduced from 88 per 1,000 live births in 1990 to 66 percent
per 1,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe should continue the surveillance of poliomyelitis and
conduct follow-up investigations on all suspected cases in order
to eliminate the remaining risk of permanent paralysis through
poliomyelitis, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
