<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Israel Ready to Resume Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said here today that his country is ready to resume the
peace talks with Syria "in the near future" only if the Syrians
want to do so.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with King Hussein of Jordan after
their talks in Royal Palace here this morning, Netanyahu said his
government would like to discuss with Syria - the main foreign
power broker in Lebanon where it maintains 35,000 troops - on
Israel's new option of "Lebanon-first," under which, Israel would
unilaterally withdraw from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister told reporters that his country
"has no territorial claims to south Lebanon," adding that Israel
wants to seek security and peace along its common borders with
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, neither Netanyahu nor King Hussein disclosed Syrian
President Hafez Al Assad's view toward the option, which the
Syrian press denounced Saturday as "an attempt to sow divisions
between Syria and Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said the solution of Lebanon would give confidence
to Syrians.
</P>
<P>
He added that Israel hopes to develop "relations of trust,
relations of stability and relations of confidence" with Syria
and seek an "agreed-upon" framework with Syrians.
</P>
<P>
To seek peace with all the Arab countries is the final
goal of his government, he asserted.
</P>
<P>
On Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, the Israeli prime minister
said that before he left Tel Aviv for Amman this morning, he
discussed with his defense minister on further easing the
closure of the Palestinian self-rule area in order to allow
thousands more Palestinians to work in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu reiterated his government's stands vis-a-vis the holy
city of Jerusalem, saying that Jerusalem will remain as a united
capital for the Jewish State.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Minister of Infrastructure Sharon's view toward
the agreed-upon Aqaba airport project represents the government's
policy, Netanyahu said the project is "a very good stimulus" to
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that his government will carry out the plan
once the feasibility study is finished.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports here said that Sharon, the rightest in the
Israeli new government, voiced his objection to an agreement
reached on converting the Aqaba airport as a joint facility to
serve both countries.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister emphasized the unity of his
government and its commitment to the peace process, saying that
"we have one government and one policy for peace."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who is here on his first official visit to Jordan
since taking office in June and the third to the kingdom since
the signing of the 1994 peace treaty, will visit the Rose-Red
city of Petra before returning home later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
