<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Cattle Safe From Lung Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Veterinary Services Director
Stuart Hargreaves said here today that Zimbabwe's cattle are safe
from the deadly lung disease which has broken out in neighboring
Botswana.
</P>
<P>
He said the disease in the north-western parts of Botswana is
bound to affect Namibia more than Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"We are fairly safe because of the area where the disease has
broken out from," he said.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of the disease has caused concern among South
African farmers because of the speed with which it spreads.
</P>
<P>
Hargreaves, however, said as a precautionary measure, any
cattle that cross the border from Botswana will have to be put on
quarantine and burnt.
</P>
<P>
The South African Transvaal Agricultural Union said at the
weekend the lung disease poses a more serious threat to its
members than the madcow disease.
</P>
<P>
Although the disease has been eradicated in South Africa eight
years ago, its outbreak in Botswana poses a new threat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
