<HEADLINE> Premier on Reform of Higher Education Administrative System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li called on officials at all levels to consider the country's
overall economic and political situation in helping improve higher
education and training more qualified personnel who can cope with
the demands of the new century, and said that more importance
should be placed on reforming the management of college education
in China.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li, who is also a Standing Committee member of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central
Committee, made the remarks on the last day of a national
conference on reform work concerning the higher education
administrative system, which opened here August 2.
</P>
<P>
Li said local education officials should tighten controls and
work out ways of restructuring administrative system, and that the
relevant central government departments should improve
coordinations in the reforms to let them develop in a still
healthier way.
</P>
<P>
Although fairly big strides have been made in reforming the
higher education administrative system over the years thanks to
efforts of the State Education Commission and other departments,
he said, its progress in reform still lags behind economic
restructuring and social development, and fails to be in line with
the socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Thus, he went on to say, "we should, on the basis of the
experiences and achievements that have so far been scored, speed
up the pace of reform and overcome difficulties and examine
priorities."
</P>
<P>
China has more than 1,000 universities and colleges, but the
number of institutions of higher learning in relation to the
population is still quite small.
</P>
<P>
Li acknowledged that greater efforts are required to get the
management of colleges to respond to the socialist market economy
and keep to the policy of revitalizing the country with science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
He also called on central government departments to take a
closer look at educational institutions with inferior qualities.
</P>
<P>
Li Lanqing, member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee and vice-premier of the State Council, also spoke at the
conference. 
</P>
