<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stricter Management Of Extra-Budgetary Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The management of extra-budgetary
funds must be improved and the misuse of these funds must be
halted immediately, according to the State Council, China's
cabinet, in a decision that it released here today.
</P>
<P>
Extra-budgetary funds have been expanding over the years, it
said.
</P>
<P>
"The use of extra-budgetary funds has escaped the overview of
the People's Congress and misuse of the funds has run rampant
because of lax management," the decision said.
</P>
<P>
"This problem has helped breed unhealthy tendencies and
corruption," it noted, adding that it has also resulted in
dispersion of state funds and disorder in public.
</P>
<P>
All areas, departments and units must implement the Budget Law
strictly and never turn budget funds into extra-budgetary funds,
the State Council said.
</P>
<P>
Fees collected and funds must be better managed to control the
size of budgetary funds, it said, noting that "collecting and
drawing extra-budgetary funds must be done in strict accordance
with laws, rules and, stipulations."
</P>
<P>
"No locality is authorized to approve funds nor is it allowed
to set up funds in the disguise of collecting fees for
administrative purposes," the decision warned. Fees and funds that
violate rules and regulations must be cancelled.
</P>
<P>
The State Council also urged all areas and departments to set
up a supervisory system and one of penalties for extra-budgetary
fund matters, and said that governments are subject to the
supervision of the local people's congress in the case of
extra-budgetary funds.
</P>
<P>
"Violators of management regulations on extra-budgetary funds
will be punished in accordance with the relevant laws and rules,"
the State Council said.
</P>
<P>
In May, China launched a campaign to tighten supervision over
extra-budgetary funds that is scheduled to last through
September. The Ministry of Finance also announced a telephone
hotline for the public to phone in when they have knowledge of
authorities' misuse of extra-budgetary funds.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that more than 400 calls to the special
"dial-a-cheat" hotline were received in the first month of
operation.
</P>
<P>
Jin Lianshu, a senior official with the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection of the Communist Party of China, has said
that extra-budgetary funds are often used to buy luxury cars and
houses, or to speculate in real estate and stocks, and that some
even end up in private hands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
