<HEADLINE> Peace Process in Snags in S. Leone: Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Although "active consultations
are going on daily with the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) in
Abidjan," recent attacks in eastern and southeastern Sierra Leone
are fuelling fears that the peace process is not working.
</P>
<P>
This was observed here today by west African diplomats
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leone government said in a statement that it is
"working on a program to create the conditions for the conclusion
of a durable peace agreement with the RUF" but did not explain
how or what form it is taking.
</P>
<P>
The statement warned "the public that durable peace is
unlikely to be achieved overnight in a savage conflict that has
lasted over five years."
</P>
<P>
A government critic, former presidential candidate for the
National Alliance Democratic Party (NADP), Yayah Sillah said in
an interview "the government should have achieved something more
concrete and meaningful after more than 100 days in power instead
of the precarious and often violated ceasefire agreement."
</P>
<P>
According to assessments made by west African diplomats, the
peace agreement ranks high in the priority list of the majority
of Sierra Leoneans.
</P>
<P>
Recent rebel attacks have resulted in the death or serious
injury of over 100 civilians.
</P>
<P>
In one attack over the weekend, rebels matcheted a treasury
clerk David Mafinda at Kainkordu in Kono district in the east,
local journalists reported.
</P>
<P>
One survivor was quoted as saying "the rebels went about the
attack in a casual way, first greeting civilians who welcomed
them as government troops and then opened fire." 
</P>
</TEXT>
