<HEADLINE> China Third In World In Mineral Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- China has invested more than 100
billion yuan in locating 160 types of minerals over the past four
decades with more than 90 percent of deposits having been
verified, putting it behind only the US and Russia in resources.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources,
China has exploited 132 kinds of mineral resources, and the
verified deposits of 20 mineral resources rank first in the world.
</P>
<P>
China has found 200,000 deposits, three-forths of which have
proven reserves, making China one of the few countries in the
world to have a wide variety of mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
The combined output of ore per year is 5.8 billion tons,
accounting for six percent of the country's total industrial
output value. Mining provides job opportunities for more 14
million people across the country. There are more than 300 cities
with mining as the pillar industry.
</P>
<P>
Iron ore production bases have been built in Anshan, Baotou,
and Panzhihua cities, and in Hainan province. Nonferrous metal
deposits are scattered in various parts of China, and Bayan Obo,
in north China's Inner Mongolia, leads the world in rare earth
output.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, Henan, Heilongjiang and Shaanxi provinces are among
the leading gold producers, and a number of large oil fields, such
as Daqing, Dagang and Jianghan brought the country's total output
of crude oil to 149 million tons in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The annual output of raw coal increased to 1.29 billion tons in
1995, ahead of all the other countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy in Kuwait Adopts Security Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The American Embassy in
Kuwait has adopted new security measures as a precaution against
possible terrorist attacks following two bomb explosions in Saudi
Arabia during the past seven months that killed 24 American
servicemen.
</P>
<P>
A new concrete security fence around the embassy compound
located in Bayan area, Kuwait city, was seen built up in recent
days. Several police cars were also found patrolling the area in
the last few days.
</P>
<P>
A diplomat of the embassy said the security fence was a
precautionary measure that was decided after a fuel truck bomb
killed 19 U.S. servicemen and injured more than 200 others at a
military housing complex in al-Khobar, Saudi Arabia in June.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. diplomat said they had not received any new threat
against the embassy, but several other security measures by the
embassy had been implemented, he added but refused to reveal them.
</P>
<P>
Huge slabs of concrete were laid around the embassy 20
meters away from the compound wall Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The American Embassy in Kuwait was struck on December 12, 1983
by a car bomb which caused the casualty of around 100 persons,
but none of them were Americans.
</P>
<P>
The embassy asked the 6,000 Americans living in Kuwait to
take caution after the bombing in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
No strikes have occurred targeting the U.S. interests and
installations in Kuwait since 1992 when the allied forces led
by the U.S. army liberated Kuwait from the occupation by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. troops in the adjoining Saudi Arabia have been hit
twice in seven months. So far no group has claimed responsibility
for the attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
