<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refuting Human Rights Watch/Asia Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A leading official from the China
Society for Human Rights Studies today said that an account by
Human Rights Watch/Asia in its July 10th report "China: the Cost
of Putting Business First" was "sheer lies."
</P>
<P>
"Human Rights Watch/Asia's unwarranted attack on China in the
Tibet issue and the crackdown on crime was 'deliberately
fabricated' and confused right with wrong," the official told a
Xinhua reporter.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Human Rights Watch/Asia gratuitously
slandered China with its accusation in a report published on
January 7, about the situation of children in Chinese child
welfare institutions.
</P>
<P>
Since that time, the official said, Chinese departments and UN
organizations that understand the actual situation of Chinese
children, along with many US adoption agencies, as well as
individual citizens who visited Chinese child welfare homes, have
refuted the lies and slanders of Human Rights Watch/Asia with the
true facts. As a result, Human Rights Watch/Asia has been
embarrassed, the official said.
</P>
<P>
A closer examination of the Human Rights Watch/Asia report
published in July revealed that it was no different from the
January report, fabricating rumors and distorting the facts, the
official said, pointing out that the contents and individual cases
in the report are "do not at all tally with the actual
situations", and referring to some of them as "slanderous rumors,"
and others as "deliberate misrepresentations".
</P>
<P>
In the report, Human Rights Watch/Asia fabricated stories,
saying that "In February 1996, the Chinese government issued a
directive to close politically active monasteries", clearly
referring to the Tibetan issue, the official pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to the relevant Chinese departments, the government
never issued such a directive, the official pointed out, noting
that Tibet now has a total of more than 1,400 monasteries and
nunneries of various kinds, and not one was closed this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refutation Of Human Rights Watch/Asia Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report also had an exaggerated account of the prison life
of Xi Yang, a former reporter for the Hong Kong newspaper Ming
Pao, saying that "he cannot eat much, vomits often, suffers from
diarrhea, has heart palpitations and skin ailments, is dizzy, and
has chronic headaches," and that "he never sees the sun."
</P>
<P>
The fact is, the official said, that when he was jailed for
stealing state secrets, Xi Yang explained in his own words that he
had certain problems with headaches and indigestion, but a
physical examinations indicated that he had no serious illness and
that all vital signs were normal.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that during his two-year prison term, Xi
Yang was in a good condition all the time, and nothing abnormal
was found. The cell Xi lived in had windows, was sun-lit, and was
well-ventilated. In addition, prisoners often participate in
outdoor activities, and Xi Yang jogged every day and often took
part in basketball and table tennis matches. Judging from these
facts, the official said that the accusation that Xi Yang "never
saw sun" in prison is a complete lie.
</P>
<P>
The Human Rights Watch/Asia report also attacked China's
"strike hard" campaign (crackdown on crime), saying that it
appears "to be more concerned with numbers than evidence," that it
"has implicitly targeted all dissidents", and that "Those arrested
in the 'strike hard' campaign are not tried before independent
judges."
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, China's struggle to deal in a lawful
manner with criminals who seriously endanger public security, from
the very beginning focused its efforts on the most heinous crimes
of violence, particularly those involving the trafficing in
narcotics and trade in firearms and dangerous gangs, the official
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Rights Watch/Asia Report Refuted (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The campaign also targets drug-trafficking, illegal firearms
dealing, kidnapping of women and children, and frequent robbery --
crimes that threaten as many residents, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that most of the criminals arrested and
tried in the crime crackdown have been involved in murder,
robbery, transportation of or trade in firearms, destruction of
property, drug-running, abducting and selling women and children,
and gang-related activities.
</P>
<P>
China has carried out the "strike hard" campaign strictly in
accordance with laws, not only as they are written, but also as
they are carried out, the official said.
</P>
<P>
As the public security departments, judicial and procuratorial
organs have adhered to the principle of strict law enforcement
with socialist ethics, the official noted, all the cases were
properly handled during the whole "strike hard" campaign.
</P>
<P>
The "strike hard" campaign won nationwide support from the
Chinese people after a number of high-profile criminals, including
some who sold nearly 600 kilograms of heroin and others who were
convicted in four murder cases, have been punished severely, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
In general, people have shown a positive reaction and extensive
support to the strike hard campaign, indicating that public
security has been greatly improved, the sense of safety increased,
and human rights guaranteed, the official said,
</P>
<P>
Human Rights Watch/Asia vigorously voices its complaints
against crime and criminals in China, and yet continues to blame
China for its severe punishment of criminals and for its actions
to safeguard human rights for the vast majority of the people, the
official pointed out.
</P>
<P>
This shows that what Human Rights Watch/Asia is concerned about
is not the human rights of the Chinese people, but the "rights of
a tiny minority of criminals to disturb the public order, to
endanger the state security and to overturn the Chinese legitimate
government," the official said, adding that it seems that Human
Rights Watch/Asia itself should be watched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Rights Watch/Asia Report Refuted (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The leading human rights official said that it appears not to
be accidental that Human Rights Watch/Asia has invented individual
criminal cases, and has concocted a report that rashly criticizes
human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
Since its founding in 1985, Human Rights Watch/ Asia has
maintained a hostile attitude against China, stirred up disputes
over human rights issues, fabricated rumors to attack and slander
China, and played henchman for Western forces that oppose China,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
While some Western nations were drafting the human rights bill
to oppose China at meetings of the UN Commission on Human Rights
held early this year, Human Rights Watch/Asia crafted an alleged
report on the situation of children in China's welfare homes, a
document that framed up lies and spread rumors that attacked the
situation of children in China and heightened the Western
countries' opposition to China's human rights situation.
</P>
<P>
The report was aired by some major media, including the Voice
of America and BBC, providing new opportunities to criticize
China, the official said.
</P>
<P>
When some Western powers rushed to create a human rights bill
against China during meetings of the UN Commission on Human Rights
in March, Watch/Asia published a follow-up report to accuse China
of potential criminal neglect in the country's child welfare homes.
</P>
<P>
There is much evidence to show that Watch/Asia's actions are
neither isolated, nor accidental, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that some human rights organizations,
called "non-governmental organizations," often take the lead in
the movement to oppose China, and are closely linked with some
Western countries.
</P>
<P>
The NGOs have, in general, played an increasingly important
role in the aspect of human rights in recent years, the official
noted, adding that this is mostly a positive trend.
</P>
<P>
However, some of the NGOs are spreading lies and rumors to
viciously attack other countries, the official said, calling on
all nations to closely monitor this activity.
</P>
<P>
The official urged NGOs in human rights to promote the
international exchange and cooperation in human rights, enhance
the mutual understanding between countries and advance world peace
and development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
