<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Makes Efforts to Mend Ties with Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh is making diplomatic
efforts to resolve pending issues with Pakistan, including the
sharing of assets.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question in parliament Sunday, Bangladeshi
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad said that Bangladesh demanded a
due share of more than 24 billion Pakistan rupees (about 780
million US dollars) in 1971 after the country was independent from
the then Pakistan and the issue has been discussed at various
levels since then between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister also noted that more than one million non-Bengalis
remained stranded in the country in the wake of Bangladesh's
independence in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Out of them, more than 500,000 people have been granted
citizenship of Bangladesh after they applied for it, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the issue of the remaining 540,000 non-Bengalis has
not been resolved though they have expressed their desire to be
repatriated to Pakistan, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
He assured MPs at the parliament session that the government is
still making diplomatic efforts for expeditious repatriation of
the stranded Pakistanis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
