<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Review Shows Low Crime Rate in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's crime rate of 1,484
 per 100,000 people is one of the lowest in the world for similar
sized or larger cities, local police said today.
</P>
<P>
Hui Ki-on, commissioner of Hong Kong Police, said in the
just-released 1995 review of the local police that last year
violent crimes such as robbery, homicide, blackmail and criminal
intimidation were all down from the 1994's figures.
</P>
<P>
The detection rate remained steady at 52 percent, "which is
very high by international standards", Hui added.
</P>
<P>
"Although the total number of crimes reported was up 4.6
percent to 91,886, this was mainly due to increases in
miscellaneous theft, wounding, serious assaults and detected drugs
 offenses," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hui attributed the achievement to the enactment of new
anti-crime laws in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the battle against crime was helped by the
"excellent and increasingly important relationship" with Chinese
law enforcement agencies which also helped the Hong Kong Police's
investigations, especially in regard to drug trafficking,
smuggling and vehicle theft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
