<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changdao County Most Affluent in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Changdao County, China's largest
offshore island county in east China's Shandong Province, has
become the country's most affluent county, with its per-capita
gross domestic product (GDP) reaching 12,600 yuan by the end of
June.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents an increase of 48.6 percent over the same
period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Made up of 32 offshore islands, Changdao is at the top of the
list of the country's 12 offshore island counties and more than
130 counties in Shandong Province in eight key economic
indexes. Of these categories, Changdao's per-capita GDP and
per-capita total savings all rank the first among China's counties.
</P>
<P>
The county's per-capita GDP is expected to exceed 30,000 yuan
this year.
</P>
<P>
Located in the offshore area between the Jiaodong and Liaodong
peninsulas, Changdao County boasts a vast surrounding sea area and
more than 200 varieties of marine life. It has a population of
more than 40,000.
</P>
<P>
Fishery is the county's leading industry. In 1995, Changdao's
total output of aquatic products reached 284,000 tons. The output
of artificial breeding stood at 200,000 tons, pushing its
per-capita quota to the highest in the country.
</P>
<P>
The county now has a 4,000-hectare breeding area in its
42,000-hectare sea vicinity.
</P>
<P>
Changdao has set up 30 ponds where artificial breeding of
salted fish fries is conducted, and more than 200 breeding
facilities for a variety of fish. There are about 100 million fish
in the county's waters.
</P>
<P>
Changdao has developed more than 30 varieties of marine
medicine and food, which sell well in both domestic and overseas
markets.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with rapid economic growth, the county has formed
five industrial groups involved in food processing, marine
medicine, shipbuilding, plastic products production, and light
industry and textiles. In 1995, its total industrial output value
reached 680 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Changdao has invested more than 700 million yuan to build
infrastructural facilities. It has constructed two 1,000-ton
roll-on/roll-off docks, opened sea transportation lines linking
Changdao to Japan and the Republic of Korea, and initiated a
marine products wholesale market.
</P>
<P>
The county has established more than 70 foreign-funded
enterprises, whose earnings from exports exceeded 30 million US
dollars in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Issues Story Book on Basic Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A story book on the Basic Law
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has been
published in Hong Kong for educating local children, a government
spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the story book was written in Chinese. With
colorful illustrations, it explains the Basic Law through everyday
life scenarios, so that children can easily understand the
importance of the Basic Law and how it relates to their daily
lives.
</P>
<P>
"The content touches on a wide range of subjects including the
promulgation of the Basic Law; the relationship between China and
Hong Kong; the basic rights and duties of residents; the use of
Chinese and English as the official languages; the design of the
SAR's flag and emblem; the political structure and the economy,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a bilingual guidebook on the Basic Law for
youngsters, "An ABC Guide to the Basic Law", will be released in
September, the spokesman added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
