<HEADLINE> Tokyo Against Capital Relocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Tokyo metropolitan government
is considering scrapping the national government's plan to
relocate capital functions out of Tokyo, Kyodo News Service
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A committee of experts has been set up by the Tokyo
metropolitan government to persuade the public that transferring
administrative, legislative and judiciary functions away from
Tokyo would be a waste of time and money, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In December last year, a National Land Agency panel issued a
report urging the construction of a new city to take on the
capital functions from 2000.
</P>
<P>
The report envisaged a city with a population of 600,000,
located between 60 kilometers to 300 km from Tokyo and called for
candidate sites to be chosen within the next two years and for the
Diet to move there by 2010.
</P>
<P>
A capital relocation bill calling for a council to be set up to
pick candidate sites was passed in June.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources say discussions at the council may be
contentious if the Tokyo metropolitan government succeeds in
getting places on it for experts opposed to relocation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Nigerians Crushed Dead Celebrating Soccer Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Tragedies over the weekend in
Nigeria trailed the country's display at the centennial Olympics
-- the clinching of the prestigious soccer gold, the first by an
African nation.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Daily Champion newspaper, a luxury bus
rammed into a crowd of jubilating youths at a Moslem-dominated
settlement in Kaduna, northern Nigeria, early Sunday, killing
four persons instantly.
</P>
<P>
The enraged youths then ordered the passengers out and set the
bus on fire.
</P>
<P>
In a village not far away, a trailer, carrying tens of
jubilant youths wielding leaves and shouting victory slogans and
songs, ran into another crowd celebrating the historic feat,
killing three persons in the process.
</P>
<P>
The two Kaduna incidents occurred at about 2:00 am on Sunday,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, an electrician in Lagos, determined to
bring electricity from a neighboring building to his house to
watch the final match between Nigeria and Argentina at a power
outrage, was electrocuted and died in hospital that night.
</P>
<P>
This was the second of soccer related tragedy in the country
in three days as an automobile mechanic also died Thursday in
Kaduna after the Brazil-Nigeria semi-final match. The cause of
death was said to be heart attack, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
