<HEADLINE> Hangzhou Attracts More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Hangzhou, the capital city of
east China's Zhejiang Province, has approved 2,204 jointly-funded
enterprises since the start of 1995, with total contractual
foreign investment reaching 2.4 billion U.S.dollars.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, Hangzhou, a well-known scenic city in
China, had 180 large joint enterprises, each of which involves at
least 10 million U.S.dollars of investment.
</P>
<P>
Joint enterprises in Hangzhou have shown marked performance and
played an increasingly important role in the city's economy in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that joint enterprises in Hangzhou have
contributed some 15 percent of the city's gross industrial output
value in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the joint enterprises established in 1995, more than
80 percent of the city's joint enterprises made profits last
year.
</P>
<P>
"More and more state enterprises of the city are interested in
finding foreign partners, not only for seeking foreign investment,
but also for updated technical know-how and products, and the
level of cooperation has been upgrading consistently," said a
senior official with the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
