<HEADLINE> Ghana, Japan Sign Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Ghana and Japan have signed three
grant agreements totalling 1.8 billion Yen (about 17 million U.S.
Dollars) for three different projects in the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
A report obtained here today said about 9.1 million Dollars of
the total amount will be used for the construction of small-scale
bridges, some 3.6 million Dollars for increased food supply while
3.8 million Dollars for rural water supply.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Ghana's foreign minister Obed Asamoah as
saying that the construction of small-scale bridges formed part
of his government's plan in rehabilitating and building an
excellent road network in the country.
</P>
<P>
The second agreement for increased food production would help
Ghana in achieving self-sufficiency in food production and
increased efforts at curtailing imports of basic food items, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the third facility was aimed at making life
more comfortable for rural dwellers, reducing water-borne
diseases and minimizing rural-urban migration. 
</P>
