<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lack of Funds Hinders Drug Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Although Thailand has achieved
considerable success in reducing narcotics production, lack of
funds, staff and legal power has kept plans to set up drug
rehabilitation centers in the country as remote as ever.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated 1.2 million drug addicts in the country,
Thailand needs to establish at least 10 rehabilitation centers
throughout the country, costing roughly 2 billion baht (80 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Since the rehabilitation of drug addicts act was passed in
1993, the Department of Probation has made annual requests for
budget, totaling 54.6 million baht (2.18 million dollars), but it
has never received a budget allocation.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the department does not have money for building
even one single center.
</P>
<P>
Beside the lack of funding, land for building these centers is
not yet available. The Treasury Department has not provided land
for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
What the Department of Probation has so far gained for the
execution of the rehabilitation program is only an agreement to
provide seven staff members.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the Office of Judicial Affairs is responsible
for establishing the centers, and in practice the task is supposed
to be carried out by the Probation Office, which, however, has
since been upgraded to a department and is no longer under the
Office of Judicial Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Lack of cooperation among various government agencies is
another problem. Although the act stipulates that the
rehabilitation centers must be administered by the director
generals and secretary generals from various agencies, such as the
police and the Food and Drug Administration, there has never been
any discussion among these relevant parties.
</P>
<P>
Some drug control officials said that the act cannot be
enforced properly because the government does not pay enough
attention to the problems of drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
When it comes to this issue, the government is too
economic-minded. They think it is useless to spend money on this,
said Jaran Pukditanakul, secretary general of the Office of
Judicial Affairs.
</P>
<P>
What is more, the act also needs amendments to tighten the
consumption of drugs to cover people who are addicted to
amphetamine and glue-sniffing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recession Persists in France in Second Quarter of 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- French economy continued to recess
in the second quarter of 1996, with a 0.1-percent drop in its
Gross National Product (GNP), according to an official economic
indicator published here today.
</P>
<P>
The Administration in Charge of Investing and Lending Public
Money (CDC) said the recession is mainly attributed to a fall in
industrial output and a rise of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The CDC estimated at the beginning of June a 0.2-percent
growth of the GNP. Industrial production fell by 2.5 percent in
May, and unemployment rate rose by 0.7 percent in June alone.
</P>
<P>
However, the CDC is optimistic that France will have a
0.4-percent growth in the GNP in the third quarter of the year and
a 0.2-percent growth in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
As to the reasons, the CDC said that "a good orientation of
short-term interest rates" has been adopted by French banks and
the GNP of the United States has gone up in the first quarter of
the year, which has direct repercussion on the French economy.
</P>
<P>
The official statistics of the GNP for the second quarter will
be published by the Institute of Statistics and Economics Study in
early September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
