<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Denies BSE-Milk Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain has denied that it is
doing research into the possibility that BSE, or mad-cow disease,
might be passed on in milk.
</P>
<P>
The claim followed the disclosure last week that BSE can be
passed from mother to calf, and that the mechanism of such
"vertical transmission" is unknown.
</P>
<P>
The Observer newspaper said on Sunday that scientists were
urgently conducting fresh research into the safety of cow's milk
amid allegations that previous experiments held to show milk
cannot be infected with BSE are unreliable and inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Agriculture Ministry Sunday called the
reports of experiments with cows' milk "absolute rubbish."
</P>
<P>
The ministry has never funded any studies to investigate
whether milk could transmit BSE to calves. "Observations in the
field support the hypothesis that it cannot," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The ministry bases its confidence on research carried out by
scientists from the Institutes for Animal Health in Edinburgh and
Berkshire, and the Central Veterinary Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
The scientists said that no signs of the disease appeared in
any of the mice.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ministry's assurances have been dismissed by some
leading scientists who claim that the experiments were poor and
inconclusive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
