<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East Countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Istanbul gold exchange traded 163.758 kilograms
of gold last year in 7,344 transactions worth over two billion
U.S. dollars, the local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the Istanbul gold exchange has been the
pillar of the program for restructuring the gold market in order
to regain the gold potential to the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul gold exchange has 52 members, of which 24 are
Turkish and foreign banks and 28 are intermediary firms for
precious metals trade.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Donor countries are expected to meet in October to
discuss the dynamics of aid to Lebanon, the first of a long series
of discussions among the members of a proposed international
consultative committee in charge of helping Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Beirut business weekly Eco News said that the Brussels
meeting will group Japan, Canada, the United States and France and
will be attended by Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and some
cabinet ministers.
</P>
<P>
It said that the meeting will test a willingness of the
U.S. to launch different aid programs through a number of
international institutions to assist the reconstruction of the
war-ravaged south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's ministerial economic group agreed at its
meeting Sunday to offer 100 investment projects to investors from
the United States, Europe, Asia and Arab countries for
implementation in many locations all over Egypt.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdy el-Banbi has announced new
national gas discoveries north of Port Said and Port Foad after
using modern technology for discovering natural gas fields. The
daily production of the new discoveries is expected to reach 69
million cubic feet, the local daily The Egyptian Gazette reported
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
