<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Filipino Babies Suffer Anemia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Anemia stalks five out of every 10
 Filipino infants and more than a quarter of the country's
population, the local press reported today, quoting statistics
from the Department of Health (DOH).
</P>
<P>
The disease, primarily caused by the lack of micro-nutrients of
Vitamin A, iodine and iron in the body, leads to mental and growth
retardation, blindness, deafness, cretinism, infant deaths,
miscarriages and stillbirth.
</P>
<P>
According to the DOH, anemia caused by iron deficiency affects
28.9 percent of the Filipinos, while infants aged between six
months and one year have the highest prevalence rate of 49
percent.
</P>
<P>
Urban areas register the lowest rate of anemia with 27.1
percent, compared with rural areas with 29.3 percent, said the
DOH.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 40 percent of the Filipinos, or 25 million
people, are living in iodine-deficient areas, where residents are
more susceptible to iron deficiency anemia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
