<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemeni Parliament Speaker Visits Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Parliament Speaker
Abdullah al-Ahmar held talks with Saudi Arabian Second Deputy
Premier Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz on Sunday night in the Red
Sea port city of Jeddah to discuss a host of the issues of common
interest, official Saudi Press Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The agency did not give any details of the talks, only said the
Yemeni speaker arrived at Jeddah, where the Saudi leaders spend
their summer times, on Sunday on an unannounced visit.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan and al-Ahmar are the co-chairmen of the higher
committee of the two countries, which was set up according to a
memorandum of understanding signed between Sanna and Riyadh in
February last year in a bid to settle border disputes and help
develop bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The joint committee is in charge of the work of six
sub-committees set up to review aspects of border re-demarcation
and development of relations. The higher committee held its first
meeting in Riyadh last December, during which both sides agreed
to hold periodical sessions every three months at each country's
capital alternatively.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ahmar's visit followed the signing of two agreements in
Jeddah last week between the two countries which were aimed at
combating drug trafficking and other crimes as well as protecting
security situation along the borders of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The interior ministers of Saudi Arabia and Yemen, after
signing the agreements, said the agreements would boost bilateral
relations and cooperation between the two Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The strained relations between the two countries have seen
relaxations in recent years. Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh
visited Saudi Arabia in June last year, his first tour to the
Kingdom in five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
