<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Kazakhstan Ready to Begin Border Demarcation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, Augest 5 (Xinhua) -- China and Kazakhstan have reached
agreement on a series of working regulations in preparation for
the official start of their border demarcation.
</P>
<P>
This came as a result of a week-long meeting, the first of the
Joint Border Survey Commission of China and Kazakhstan, which
concluded in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said the July 29-August 5 meeting was
held in "a friendly atmosphere and a truth-seeking spirit."
</P>
<P>
The meeting was a follow-up to the Sino-Kazak Agreement on
Border Demarcation, which was signed by Chinese Premier Li Peng
and Kazak President Nursultan Nazarbayev on April 26, 1994, in Alma
Ata, and took effect on September 11, 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the Joint Border Survey Commission
of China and Kazakhstan is responsible for organizing and carrying
out border survey, marking, and measuring and drawing topographic
maps that define the border areas.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed at the meeting on matters concerning
the fieldwork of border demarcation which will begin next year.
The second meeting of the joint commission is expected to be held
in Alma Ata at the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
