<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia, Africa Seek Cooperation in Desert Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Officials from Asian and African
countries and the United Nations gathered in Beijing today to
probe ways to fight desertification on the two continents, and to
improve their cooperation for the project.
</P>
<P>
About 30 officials participating in the Asia-Africa Forum on
Combating Desertification will hear countries report on their
efforts to prevent desertification in China, Mali, India and
Botswana.
</P>
<P>
During the six-day event, the leaders are expected to create a
framework that will guide Asian-African cooperation in the fight
against desertification.
</P>
<P>
They also are scheduled to visit desert control projects in
Inner Mongolia in north China on August 7 and 8.
</P>
<P>
Xu Youfang, Minister of Forestry, told the forum, which is
jointly organized by United Nations, Japan and China, that Asia
and Africa have the largest and most severely-affected areas of
desertification.
</P>
<P>
He said many Asian and African countries have become
knowledgeable about the problem, and have developed many techniques
during their prolonged efforts to curb desertification.
</P>
<P>
"The present Asia-Africa forum is a major action taken by the
Asian and African countries to implement the UN Convention to
Combat Desertification and to carry out regional cooperation in
the Asian-African region," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Over one billion people in the world are directly threatened by
desertification, and 135 million of them are likely to lose their
land in the immediate future, the minister quoted the Secretariat
of the UN Convention to Combat Desertification as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 400 million people in China are threatened by
desertification, and desertified area in China accounts for one
third of the country's total, Vice-minister Zhu Guangyao told the
forum.
</P>
<P>
To make matters worse, the desertified area is expanding at
2,100 sq km each year, Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, China started construction on the "three north"
shelter belt project across northwest, north and northeast China,
in an attempt to ward off the problem.
</P>
<P>
China has since afforested 16.63 million ha of land in those
regions, which has provided protection for 11 million ha of
farmland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Trade Deficit Expands in First Half of '96 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel's trade deficit,
excluding diamonds, reached 5.8 billion U.S. dollars in the first
half of this year, a 10.3 percent rise over the same period last
year, the Central Bureau of Statistics said today.
</P>
<P>
Of the total trade deficit, 3.4 billion dollars was built up
with the European Union (EU), 1.3 billion dollars with the U.S.,
and 500 million dollars with its Asian trade partners, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The growth in the deficit with the U.S. increased by 70
percent, while smaller increases were registered with the EU and
European Free Trade Association (EFTA) countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the deficit with Asian countries shrank by some 15
percent, as exports increased by 10 percent in relation to
imports, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's total imports, also excluding diamonds, stood at 12.7
billion dollars in the first half of this year, approximately half
coming from the EU and a quarter from the U.S., it said.
</P>
<P>
The imports increased by 1 billion dollars over the same period
of last year, comprising a rise of 550 million dollars from the
U.S., 400 million dollars from the EU and 120 million dollars from
Asia. Within Asia, however, imports from the Far East reduced by
some 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, this country's exports excluding diamonds reached 7
billion dollars in the first half, 40 percent of which went to the
EU, 25 percent to the U.S., and 13 percent to Asia, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The exports increased by 420 million dollars over the same
period of last year, due mainly to a 200 million dollar increase
in exports to Asia. But exports to EFTA countries shrank by 37
million dollars, and to the U.S. by 26 million, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
