<HEADLINE> Elephant Population Grows in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The elephant population in Zambia
had grown steadily to 24,232 from 20,824 in 1994, thanks to the
major successes scored by the Department of Wildlife Services in
the fight against poaching.
</P>
<P>
Although the department cannot eradicate poaching completely,
it has managed to bring it under control in most areas of the
country, wildlife services public relations officer Tennyson
Musimuko said on Sunday at the Zambia agricultural and commercial
show in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Musimuko said that the department has just completed training
six officers to run intelligence unit which was created in
September last year to boost the fight against the scourge.
</P>
<P>
"You can't completely eradicate poaching but we have managed
to control it as can be seen from the growth in elephant
population. We have also stepped up control of human encroachment
in game management areas," Musimuko said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
