<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shift to Indirect Financial Macro Control Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A maturing market economy and a
rapidly-developing banking sector have combined to enable China's
central bank to shift from direct to indirect macro-financial
control.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that in recent years, the People's Bank of China
has been working to make such a switch.
</P>
<P>
"The conditions for such a shift have now become ripe, thanks
to the establishment of a market economy system, financial
development and an improving macro-economic control method," an
expert said.
</P>
<P>
Increases in the number of financial institutions and
instruments have brought down the proportion of loans by
specialized state-owned banks in the overall social credit scale,
the expert explained, adding that the proportion was down from 75
percent in 1993 to 62 percent in April this year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's role in bill discounting and open market
operation in treasury bonds, coupled with the formation of a
unified national interbank money market and others, has made
indirect financial macro control a viable choice, experts say.
</P>
<P>
As specialized state-owned banks turn into commercial entities
and financial competition toughens, the commercial banks will
become more sensitive to the central bank's monetary policy
signals, according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
The creation of a modern enterprise system will also make
Chinese firms, the target of macro financial control, more
sensitive to the central bank's policy signals, they add.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Arrives in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu arrived here today for a one-day official visit to
Jordan, his first after taking office in June.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Information Minister Marwan Muasher said today that
Netanyahu's talks in Amman will be important both for the Middle
East peace process and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is interested in pushing forward the peace process and
resuming peace negotiations on all tracks as soon as possible, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The information minister added that many bilateral issues will
be discussed during the visit, especially Jordan's trade
cooperation with the West Bank and Israel and the water issue.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein is expected to discuss with the Israeli prime
minister the outcome of talks he held with Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad in Damascus Saturday.
</P>
<P>
No details have emerged from the five-hour talks in the Syrian
capital, because most of the discussions were held between the
two leaders behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
However, it is believed that one of the key topics that King
Hussein and President Assad discussed was a so-called "Lebanon
First" option under which Israel is reportedly offering a
unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The king told reporters upon his return home that he was not
carrying any message from President Assad to Netanyahu but he
stood ready to offer whatever help he could offer if asked to do
so in the cause of comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to local media and Israeli press reports, Netanyahu
outlined the "Lebanon First" option to the king during a secret
meeting in London 10 days ago, and asked the king to mediate with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
But Damascus, the main foreign power broker in Lebanon where
it maintains a force of 35,000 troops, publicly rejected the
option Saturday, describing the deal as "an attempt to sow
divisions between Syria and Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian-Israeli front, Jordan will raise the issue
of an Israeli government decision last Friday to lift restriction
on building settlements in the West Bank and seek explanations
from Netanyahu, sources here said.
</P>
<P>
On the bilateral ties, Jordanian officials expected real
promises and tangible results from the summit meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
"Much ground has already been covered in advancing the
implementation of the provisions in the Jordanian-Israeli peace
treaty," said an official, quoted by today's English-language
daily Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
"We expect definite decisions to emerge during Mr. Netanyahu's
visit," said the official.
</P>
<P>
The official did not elaborate, but he was obviously referring
to the delay in fulfilling Israel's obligations to Jordan under
the October 1994 peace treaty, particularly in providing water to
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is also concerned about reports that the government of
Netanyahu might backtrack on an agreement on converting Aqaba
airport as a joint facility to serve both countries.
</P>
<P>
During today's talks, King Hussein and Netanyahu are expected
to discuss bureaucratic obstacles that Israel has placed in the
way of Jordan's trade with the Jewish State as well as the
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Television over the weekend,
Netanyahu implicitly admitted that there were such hurdles but
said they need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
Comments by Jordanian officials here indicated that they were
highly optimistic that significant progress could be made in all
the outstanding issues on a bilateral level during today's talks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister has visited the Kingdom twice since
Jordan and Israel signed the peace treaty in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
