<HEADLINE> World Bank Proposes Economic Strategy for Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has proposed to the
Bangladeshi government a four-step strategy to help it
re-establish a sound macroeconomic framework, including realistic
programs and flexible foreign exchange management.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was contained in the World Bank's recent report --
"Bangladesh: an Agenda for Action" -- which was published here
today.
</P>
<P>
The bank urged the Bangladeshi government to maintain a steady
increase in fiscal revenues and to keep the annual development
program in a realistic size and ensure the high quality of
projects.
</P>
<P>
The report said the government's monetary policy must strike a
right balance between containing inflation and not holding back
the growth of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
It said that the government's management of the foreign
exchange rate must remain flexible and sensitive to the country's
international competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank urged the government to refrain from the
temptation to re-establish ad hoc control in areas such as trade
and investment policies, where market-based approaches are already
in place.
</P>
<P>
The bank requested the Bangladeshi government to commit as soon
as possible to a three-year policy framework in coordination with
the bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to ensure the
consistency and correct sequencing of the four steps.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
