<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Protests Israel over Lifting Ban on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today protested the Israeli
government's decision to lift ban on settlement construction,
the local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a message sent to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, Arafat expressed his concern about the fate of future
peace process in light of Israel's decision to lift the freeze on
settlement activity in the Palestinian territories, Israel Radio
said.
</P>
<P>
The local Hebrew newspapers reported that Arafat also hoped
that the Israeli forces would redeploy soon from the flashpoint
West Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
This is the first reaction from Arafat since the Israeli
Cabinet decided Friday to end a four-year freeze, imposed by the
previous Labor government, on construction of settlements.
Netanyahu described the move as a step to "correct the
discrimination against Jewish settlement" in the territories.
</P>
<P>
The decision has aroused grave concerns from the international
conmmunity, especially from the Arab world which warned against
the serious damage on the future peace process.
</P>
<P>
Members of the PNA discussed the Israeli government's decision
Friday hours after its announcement. PNA Member Saeb Erekat
warned that settlement expansion "is a de facto cancellation of
peace".
</P>
<P>
Israel said it had informed the U.S., Jordan and Egypt of its
plan on the settlement. But Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
warned the peace process could be in danger if the settlement
construction plan was implemented.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to calm the anger at the decision on settlement, the
Israeli Foreign Ministry has drawn up a document aimed at
explaining to foreign governments the need to expand Jewish
settlements.
</P>
<P>
The ministry claimed the decision was made to meet the
increasing housing demand as a result of the natural growth of the
Jewish population in the territories. It also promised that the
new decision would not lead to new appropriation of Palestinian
lands.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has yet formalized a plan on the
question of pulling troops out from Hebron, though it has signaled
its willingness to honor the Oslo peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo agreements, Israeli forces were to have
completed redeployment by the end of March. But Israel delayed
its pullout after the Islamic fundamentalist militants launched a
series of suicide bombing attacks that killed 58 people inside
Israel from late February to early March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
