<HEADLINE> "May 4" Prize for Journalists Given </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- China's annual top award for
journalistic articles about young people was presented in Beijing
today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 135 entries, including printed stories, photographs and
television news broadcasts, won the prize for dozens of national
and local news media across the country, including Xinhua News
Agency, "People's Daily," "China Daily" and China Central
Television.
</P>
<P>
The "May 4" Prize, named for the Youth Day celebration held
annually in China on that day, honors the year's outstanding
journalistic reporting that focuses on youth. This is the second
year the prize has been given.
</P>
<P>
Judges from the Central Committee of Communist Youth League of
China (CYLC), the All-China Journalists' Association (ACJA), the
Propaganda Department of the Central Committee of the Chinese
Communist Party, the Press and Publication Administration of
China, and major media received nearly 300 entries recommended by
48 local and national media representatives.
</P>
<P>
Chen Tanqiang, a contest judge, said at today's news conference
to announce the winners that the overall quality of the reports,
which were selected from across the country, was good.
</P>
<P>
He said the reports vividly represent the lives of today's
young people and also illustrate China's reform and opening up
drive. He said that several of the reports would have a great
influence on the country's youth.
</P>
<P>
Liu Peng, secretary of the CYLC Central Committee's
secretariat, said that efforts to work for the betterment of
China's youth can be positively guided by the media, and in turn
the media can benefit from the creativity of young people.
</P>
<P>
Liu said he hoped that the media will continue to help produce
an environment that is conducive to the development and
improvement of young people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
