<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Disease Outbreaks in C. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A coffee disease devastated
several plantations in central Uganda, a report reaching here
today said.
</P>
<P>
The deadly disease rampant at Kiboga, some 130 kilometers
northwest of here, is similar to the common armillaria#,but is
more destructive than it, Stiphen Mubiru, Kiboga agricultural
department officer, said.
</P>
<P>
The disease breaking out now at Kiboga causes the rotting of
the root system, degeneration of the plant, fading of color in
the leaves and wilting as well as eventual dying of the tree in
four to seven days.
</P>
<P>
Kiboga agricultural sector had advised farmers to uproot the
infected coffee trees, but the farmers refused.
</P>
<P>
Uprooting and burning of the infected coffee trees is the
only way to save the others, Mubiru said, adding that the
affected trees cannot be cured. Replanting is normally done after
a minimum of 24 months.
</P>
<P>
Coffee is the number one foreign exchange earner in Uganda,
which is the second largest coffee exporter in Africa, just after
Cote d'Ivoire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
