<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-Fire Monitoring Committee on S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 5 (Xinhua) -- A five-state committee in charge
of overseeing the cease-fire in south Lebanon, which was
established by an understanding reached between Lebanon and
Israel last April, is to meet in Cyprus Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Beirut conservative daily An-Nahar said this morning that
the cease-fire monitoring committee is to meet for the first time
after France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States
completed the nomination of their representatives to the
committee.
</P>
<P>
France, Israel and the U.S. appointed both diplomatic and
military representatives while Syria and Lebanon refrained from
appointing diplomats on the grounds of the security nature of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. State Department official, David Krinly, is to preside
at the committee meetings in accordance with an agreement between
Paris and Washington on a five-month rotation of the chairmanship
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Their first meeting will be limited to discussions on the
group's regulations of work, its missions and the observers to be
sent to south Lebanon, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The April understanding was brokered by the United States
following a 16-day-long Israeli blitz in south Lebanon in which
more than 200 Lebanese, most of them civilians, were killed and
400 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, guerrillas of the pro-Iranian Lebanese
Hezbollah, or Party of God, were banned from firing horrible
Katyusha rockets at the Jewish settlements at the Galilee
panhandle in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
The understanding also prohibited the Israeli forces and
Hezbollah guerrillas from attacking from or at civilian areas in
south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
