<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down On Phony Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- As Chinese Renminbi yuan enjoys
greater international prestige, criminal cases related to making,
selling and spending counterfeit versions of the currency have
increased.
</P>
<P>
Chinese police solved over 5,000 counterfeit money-related
cases in 1995, confiscating phony banknotes with a combined face
value of about 100 million Renminbi yuan, a rise of 31 percent
over the previous year, according to the information disclosed by
the Ministry of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
Chen Qing, section chief of the Department of Economic
Protection of the ministry, said that most of the fake money is
made overseas, especially in Taiwan, and transported to the
Chinese mainland through underground channels.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is scheduled to intensify its crackdown on phony
money deals in the southeastern coastal areas, southwestern border
areas and certain provinces in central China, where counterfeiting
is rampant, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The National People's Congress Standing Committee, China's top
legislature, adopted the Decision on Punishing Criminals
Disrupting Financial Order on June 30 last year, which stipulates
the penalties for selling, possessing and using phony bills, and
provides a better legal basis for the police to control the fake
money-related activities.
</P>
<P>
In light of worsening phony money crimes, the Ministry of
Public Security set up a special agency to help organize,
coordinate and direct the anti-counterfeiting effort across the
country, Chen noted.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has also made surveys and investigations in
regions where counterfeiting crime occurs most, and has collected
considerable first-hand data that will aid police in their battle
against such crimes.
</P>
<P>
Counterfeiting reaches all areas of life, Chen said, so the
Ministry of Public Security has intensified cooperation with
departments of finance, industry and commerce, customs and
communications.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese police will also strengthen its
cooperation with Interpol and police organizations in the regions
of Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao to fight against counterfeiters, so
as to prevent phony money from being smuggled into the country.
</P>
<P>
A campaign that aims to teach citizens how to distinguish phony
bills from the real thing is expected to be implemented soon, Chen
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
