<HEADLINE> Farmers' Net Income Up in Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The per capita net income of
farmers in east China's Fujian Province soared to 1,239 yuan
(149.2 US dollars) in the first half of this year, a 6.4 percent
increase over 1995's January-June period.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that Fujian is approaching its goal to help
farmers live a relatively comfortable life by the end of the
century.
</P>
<P>
The State Statistical Bureau has set 16 norms to evaluate the
living standards of rural residents. They include the possession
of durable goods, life expectancy, living space and the number of
educated adults.
</P>
<P>
Increasing farmers' income was placed at the top of the
government's agenda. To achieve this, the Fujian government
stepped up investment in agriculture, raised the purchasing price
of grain, developed fruit and vegetable growing and aquatic
production and accelerated rural industry.
</P>
<P>
To abide by its policy of achieving common prosperity, the
province has increased government allocation for its 500,000
people with a per capita annual income of less than 750
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
