<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Children Grow Taller </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese school children are on
average five to six centimeters taller than they were 10 years
ago thanks to improved diet and the eradication of a
growth-inhibiting disease, an official report said today.
</P>
<P>
The youngsters' growth co-incides with the 10 years of economic
renovation and reform carried out in the country and, says the
report, is heartening news for a nation long consigned to the
bottom of the height league among southeast Asian countries due to
continual war and associated poverty.
</P>
<P>
This 10-year period is the first time growth in average height
among Vietnamese children has been recorded since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The National Institute of Nutrition, which carried out the
report, said the findings are encouraging for the Ministry of
Education and Training which has set a national adult average
height target of 165 cm for men and 160 cm for women, an increase
over the current averages of 160 cm for men and 152 cm for women.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for the spurt in children's height include an
improved diet, at least in many urban areas, and most
significantly an eradication of xerophthalmia, a condition caused
by vitamin A deficiency and which can stunt growth.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in history, Vietnam has become
xerophthalmia free," said a doctor from the National Institute of
Nutrition. "The desire to be tall, strong and healthy is not only
an official concern, but also the people's wish," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government is determined that Vietnamese should be taller
after years of war and associated poverty, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
