<HEADLINE> Lebanese, Syrian Presidents to Meet in Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi is
to leave here this morning for Damascus to meet with his Syrian
counterpart Hafez al-Assad, the second meeting between the two
leaders in 20 days.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed official sources in Beirut said that Hrawi and
al-Assad will discuss the latest developments in the region and
the upcoming parliamentary elections in Lebanon, which is to start
on August 18.
</P>
<P>
The summit is to be followed by a visit to the Syrian capital
by Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik al-Hariri where he will meet
Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam. Hariri is coming back
from a trip in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Local political observers noted that the consultations between
the Syrian and Lebanese leaders come amid intensive contacts
between regional leaders on the so-called "Lebanon First"
proposal put forward by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The proposal provides for an unilateral Israeli withdrawal
from the so-called "security zone" in south Lebanon in exchange
for a disarmament of the Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party
of God, and a mechanism to guarantee the security on the
Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
The Shiite fundamentalist Hezbollah spearheads a guerrilla
warfare against the Israeli occupation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
the Lebanese leaders refused the "Lebanon First" proposal out
of a suspicion that the proposal was aimed at driving a wedge
between the Syrian and Lebanese tracks of the peace negotiations
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
After a visit to Damascus Saturday, Jordanian King Hussein is
to hold a meeting today with Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu in
Amman.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein denied that he had been asked by the Syrian
president to convey a message to the Israeli prime minister, and
declined to make a comment on the "Lebanon First" proposal.
</P>
<P>
Another summit is reportedly to be held in Cairo in two days
between Syrian President al-Assad and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak. 
</P>
