<HEADLINE> Thousands of Zimbabwe's Textile Jobs Now Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Zimbabwean textile
jobs are now safe after South Africa agreed to slash tariffs on
Zimbabwean textiles and clothing from up to 90 percent to no more
than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The daily Herald paper said today the textile and clothing
industry welcomes the concessionary agreement so much that it
will be translated into the amended Zimbabwe-South Africa
bilateral accord for implementation in early September.
</P>
<P>
The deal, struck at the weekend after years of protracted
negotiations, effectively reopens the South African market to
those Zimbabwean manufacturers who are able to compete on price,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview in Harare yesterday, Zimbabwe's Minister of
Industry and Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira described the weekend
agreement as a "breakthrough in our relations with South Africa".
</P>
<P>
Jonee Blanchfield from Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries
heaped praises on Shamuyarira, saying he had done a "sterling
job" for the Zambabwean clothing and textile industry.
</P>
<P>
She said the agreement will see new energy being put back into
the industry to enable it to return to profitability.
</P>
<P>
Some 31 Zimbabwean clothing firms have gone out of business
since January last year, leaving more than 3,000 people jobless.
</P>
</TEXT>
