<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Give Relief to Shrimp Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
decided to give relief to shrimp farmers to help them overcome
losses in the outbreak of the incurable "white spot" disease,
official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The relief, a total of 6.4 million U.S. dollars, will be
granted to over 870 shrimp farmers in an area of 6,000 acres, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
These shrimp farmers, making an annual income of 36.4 million
U.S. dollars, provide employment to 40,000 people.
</P>
<P>
As the disease is irremediable, affected farms have to be
dredged up and refilled with fresh water.
</P>
<P>
Some farms have already closed down because of high costs to
fight the disease, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They added that further relief is being considered in the form
of re-scheduling bank loans for the shrimp farmers and a
10-percent duty waiver on shrimp feed.  
</P>
