<HEADLINE> Nine Islands "Missing" From Jakarta's Tourist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- At least nine islands among the
the Thousand Islands, a popular tourist attraction in north
Jakarta, are now gone due to widespread disregard of the
environment and ecology, the Antara news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted Jakarta Governor Surjadi Soedirdja as saying
recently that the islands are gone because of constant fishing
using dynamites and lethal chemical substances, coral poaching,
mining activities, oil dumping and cutting of mangrove trees.
</P>
<P>
The cluster of islands, or the Thousand Islands in the north of
Jakarta, consists of 120 isles.
</P>
<P>
Soedirdja did not name the "missing islands."
</P>
<P>
To better preserve the Thousand Islands, one of Jakarta's
popular tourist destinations, the Jakarta municipality will
install among others a high-technology waste treatment system in
north Jakarta to prevent the area's waste from flowing to the sea
and affecting the islands, he said.
</P>
<P>
Soedirdja also called for more active conservation activities
in the islands concerned.  
</P>
