<HEADLINE> Ricoh Makes More Low-priced Digital Cameras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 5 (Xinhua)-- Japan's Ricoh Co. has increased the
monthly output of its new-version digital still cameras to 25,000
units, over 3.5 times more than the present output of 7,000,
according to Kyodo News Service here today.
</P>
<P>
Ricoh, one of the leading precision instrument makers in Japan,
entered the digital camera market in April 1995 with the DC-1
camera, which stores data on a 24-megabit flash memory chip. The
camera can transfer still, moving images and audio data onto
personal computers (PC). It can also be linked to a television set
to monitor still and moving scenes with sound.
</P>
<P>
As more and more people use PCs and the global PC communication
network, Internet, there is a growing demand for digital cameras
worldwide. To meet the demand and cut cost, Ricoh last month
launched the DC-2 with all features of the DC-1 except for the
functions of storing data on a memory chip. The DC-2 sells for
69,800 yen (640 U.S. dollars) per unit, only half the price of the
DC-1.
</P>
<P>
The company is making the 35-millimeter digital still cameras
at its manufacturing base in Taiwan but sells them in the Japanese
market. It plans to start the sale of the hi-tech cameras in the
United States in October, with a monthly sales target of 5,000
cameras. 
</P>
</TEXT>
