<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Chinese Medicine to Target Global Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 5 (Xinhua) -- China will soon launch the
"Hongyang Project," a national program to accelerate the entry of
traditional Chinese medicine into the world market, "China Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The State Science and Technology Commission and the State
Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine are carrying out
research to determine working principles and appropriate actions,
the paper says.
</P>
<P>
The research will be carried out to enhance the quality of
traditional Chinese medicines and to create some best-brand
medicines.
</P>
<P>
The completed program will later be submitted to the State
Council for final approval.
</P>
<P>
Policy makers anticipate that at least two kinds of new
medicines developed from traditional Chinese medicines will be
officially registered in Western countries by the end of the
century. They also hope that traditional Chinese medical theory
will be accepted in these countries.
</P>
<P>
In the draft program, the State Science and Technology
Commission and the State Administration of Traditional Chinese
Medicine suggest the central government allocate special funds or
make a loan to support the project.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, a special office composed of officials and experts
from all related departments should be established to provide
guidance.
</P>
<P>
With fewer side-effects than many Western medicines and its
success rate in treating some chronic ailments like cancer,
cardiovascular disease and AIDS, traditional Chinese medicine has
attracted more and more foreign enthusiasts in recent years, said
the official who is now in charge of the "Hongyang Project"
research.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily" reported that China has established exchanges and
co-operative relations in the field with more than 30 countries
and regions worldwide. Each year, about 1 billion US dollars worth
of traditional Chinese medicine, mostly medicinal materials, is
exported to 130 countries and regions, mostly to Japan, and Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan regions.
</P>
<P>
Yet, due to differences between the theory of Western and
traditional Chinese medicines, the latter are not allowed to be
registered in some Western nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Opens Bill Re-discounting to Nearby Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai branch of the
People's Bank of China, the central bank, has become the first in
the country to open bill re-discounting to clients from other
cities.
</P>
<P>
Starting this month, Shanghai has opened bill re-discounting to
nine major cities in the Yangtze River Delta -- Nanjing, Wuhan,
Changsha, Chengdu, Nanchang, Ningbo, Hangzhou, Hefei and Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
In the past, bill re-discounting in China was restricted to the
same administrative region.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that the latest move indicates that Shanghai is
emerging as a financial center in the Yangtze River Delta and
also in China.
</P>
<P>
It will promote economic and financial cooperation between
Shanghai and the Yangtze River Delta, one of the most
economically-dynamic areas in China, observers say.
</P>
<P>
They also say that opening bill re-discounting to neighboring
areas will greatly speed up capital circulation and help provide
more funding for large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the value of bills discounted by banks in
Shanghai grew by a net 2.18 billion yuan (about 260 million US
dollars) in the first half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
