<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Not to Renew Friendship Treaty with India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Foreign Minister Abdus
Samad Azad Sunday told the parliament that the new government will
not renew the existing Bangladesh-India friendship treaty to be
expired on March 18, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government of Awami League (AL) feels that there is no
necessity to renew the 25-year friendship treaty in view of the
prevailing regional and international political context, the
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
The contentious friendship treaty, signed by the then AL
government shortly after the independence of Bangladesh from
Pakistan in 1971, is described by the opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party as an "accord of slavery".
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister denied the accusation, saying that there
is nothing secret in the treaty and it was discussed in the then
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Samad Azad also said that the new government had taken a bold
initiative to resolve the water-sharing problem with India and
will be able to realize the "right share" of the Ganges water.
</P>
<P>
"It's an issue of national importance," he called upon all
political parties, including the opposition in parliament, to
extend cooperation in resolving the long-standing problem.
</P>
