<HEADLINE> Incentives Urged to Lure Indonesia's Geothermal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Geothermal
Association has called on the government to provide tax incentives
for investors to build geothermal power plants to accelerate the
country's energy diversification program.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Post today quoted Chairman of the association
Prijanto as saying that "we hope the government will provide tax
incentives to encourage investors to develop geothermal energy.
But it will be even better if the government can grant them tax
holidays."
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been trying to diversify its commercial energy
away from oil which still dominates the country's energy sources.
</P>
<P>
Prijanto said that using geothermal energy to produce 1,000
megawatts (mw) of electricity can save about 300 million barrels
of oil.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, investors' main concern is the high
capital costs and the high risks in developing geothermal power
plants.
</P>
<P>
He said that until now only 309.5 mw of Indonesia's total
potential capacity of 19.600 mw of geothermal sources have been
developed by three geothermal power stations in Java.
</P>
<P>
According to him, four projects are being negotiated by
state-owned Pertamina oil company and state electricity company
with private investors.
</P>
<P>
"If all the projects start operating at their full capacity by
the end of 1999, the total capacity of geothermal power stations
will reach 1,500.5 megawatts," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's electricity demand grows at 12 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned electricity company, which has offered private
investors the chance to develop power stations under
build-operate-and-transfer schemes, plans to raise its generating
capacity from the current 13,129 mw to around 39,000 mw by 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
