<HEADLINE> Indian PM Denies Tapping of Phones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister H.D. Deve
Gowda Sunday told a delegation of senior Congress party leaders
that there was no element of truth in reports that their
telephones were being tapped and their homes were under
surveillance by intelligence agencies, the Hindustan Times said
today.
</P>
<P>
Stoutly denying the reports, Gowda assured the leaders,
including former minister of external affairs Pranab Mukherjee,
that he had checked up with his office and there was not truth in
such reports.
</P>
<P>
The reports which appeared in a local publication said that the
personal telephones of Congress party President P.V. Narasimha Rao
and other party leaders considered close to him were being tapped
by the intelligence agencies on the orders of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Gowda's meeting with the Congress party
delegation, Home Secretary K. Padmanabhaiah denied in a statement
the reports on phone tapping, calling such reports as a "total
fabrication."
</P>
<P>
He said there was no element of truth in the reports and "these
are mischievous and motivated."
</P>
<P>
The Congress party leaders said following the prime minister's
assurance, they had decided not to further press the matter.
</P>
<P>
They said "we have to go by the prime minister's word although
we are not fully satisfied."
</P>
<P>
Deve Gowda's prompt initiative in dealing with the issue of
surveillance and telephone tapping was believed to have helped
lower the temperature which was rising sharply over growing
tensions between the ruling United Front and the Congress party
which is supporting the government from the outside.  
</P>
