<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Relaxes Local Borrowings by Foreign Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Central Bank has
decided to lift the ceiling on local borrowings by foreign
companies to allow them more leeway in obtaining funds from local
financial institutions starting January 1997, local reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Central Bank Gabriel Singson said in a
statement that the lifting of the borrowing ceiling will align
monetary policies with the deregulated financial environment and
the government's program to attract more foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government had formerly required foreign
companies to maintain a debt-to-equity ratio (d/e) of 70-30
percent or 60-40 percent, depending on their industry categories,
in determining the amount of loanable funds that these firms can
source from local banks and nonbanks.
</P>
<P>
This rule was meant to prevent foreign firms from crowding
local corporations out of the limited resources in the financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
However, recent studies by the Central Bank indicated that
foreign companies are relying less than expected on local banks
for loans, which, monetary authorities said, justifies the easing
of the regulation.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the lifting of the ceiling on peso borrowings,
the government has also liberalized repatriation of investments
and remittance of profits or dividends, the reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' International Reserves Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' net international
reserves (NIR) surged by 52 percent to 8.4 billion U.S. dollars in
the first semester of 1996 from 5.5 billion U.S. dollars in the
same period last year, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank attributed the substantial growth
to more inflows than outflows in the country's banking system.
</P>
<P>
The NIR is composed of the Central Bank's assets which include
its gross international reserves and its reserve position with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) minus its short-term liabilities
and IMF drawdowns.
</P>
<P>
A continued uptrend of the NIR gives the Central Bank more
elbow room in managing surges in foreign exchange flows in the
country, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Central Bank said the high NIR level for the
first half of the year gives the country a greater capacity to pay
off its foreign loans and finance imports.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Philippines experienced a fall in NIR in the
first semester to roughly 5.9 billion U.S. dollars as
international investors pulled out from emerging markets due to
Mexico's currency crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, MNLF Resolve Stumbling Blocks to Peace Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Muslim MORO National Liberation Front (MNLF) have reached
agreement in principle on two contentious issues hindering a final
peace pact, the local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was a major fruit of the "meeting of minds" between
Executive Secretary Ruben Torres and MNLF Chairman Nur Misuari in
Sulu, Mindanao, on July 31, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The two stumbling blocks are to the creation of a regional
security force and the integration of MNLF regulars into the Armed
Forces of the Philippines (AFP) and the Philippine National Police
(PNP).
</P>
<P>
A few days before the July 31 meeting, the government had
already conceded to the MNLF's demand for the integration of 5,500
MNLF regulars into the AFP and another 2,000 Muslim rebels into
the PNP.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the two sides also agreed in principle on the
creation of a special regional security force in the Autonomous
Region for Muslim Mindanao (ARMM) by 1999, which was also attended
by members of the Organization of Islamic Countries (OIC).
</P>
<P>
The consensus on the integration and regional security has
paved the way for the government and the MNLF to proceed to
discuss a final peace agreement in the Indonesian capital of
Jakarta in August, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
It also allows the two parties to finalize the creation of the
Southern Philippines Council for Peace and Development (SPCPD),
the reports added.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta meeting is likely to be held in the third or fourth
week of August after the Senate concludes its inquiry into the
Mindanao peace process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rice Stock Reaches 2.7 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's total rice stock has
reached 2.7 million tons, with 1.2 million tons of domestic rice
procurements, said an official of the state logistics agency
BULOG, according to reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Semarang in Central Java on Sunday, BULOG's Deputy
Director for Supervision Irfansyah expressed optimism that the
agency will be able to achieve the procurement target of two
million tons for the current 1996-97 fiscal year, which ends next
March.
</P>
<P>
Irfansyah said Indonesia's current rice stock of 2.7 million
tons -- of which some 1.5 million tons came from imports -- is
enough to guarantee food security in the country before the
upcoming general elections in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of this year, domestic procurement is expected to
reach 1.5 million tons. I am optimistic that this can be
achieved, especially with the start of the government's
one-million hectare rice field megaproject," Irfansyah said.
</P>
<P>
Under the megaproject, one million hectares of peat land in
central Kalimantan will be converted into agricultural land, most
of which will become rice fields.
</P>
<P>
BULOG, established in 1967, is charged with maintaining the
price stability of basic food commodities such as rice, sugar and
flour, through buffer stocking and market interventions.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, a major rice producer in the world, turned to
imports in late 1994 after unfavorable weather conditions hit
domestic harvests. The country first achieved self-sufficiency in
rice in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Indonesia produced 49 million tons of unhusked rice,
compared with 46.4 million tons in 1994 and 48.14 million tons in
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
