<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug-related Crime Soars in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Drug-related crime in Germany rose
82 percent in the first half of this year, as more addicts turn to
crime to pay for their habit, a German official said today.
</P>
<P>
An average of 14 crimes a day related to drugs took place in
the first six months of 1996, Eduard Lintner, commissioner of the
federal drugs bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The number of people dying from drug abuse rose 10 percent to
753 in the first half of this year and the number of heroin
addicts also rose 10 percent to 5,472, government statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Lintner said the high price of drugs has led many addicts to
ruin, and such people try every way they can to satisfy their
addiction, including turning to crime.
</P>
<P>
The German government and local authorities are now considering
changing the current policy on the control of drugs.
</P>
<P>
They have called on society, especially the mass media, schools
and families, to enhance their sense of social responsibility to
try to stem the growing tide of drug users, particularly among the
young. 
</P>
</TEXT>
