<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Olympic Games Close with Flag Passing to Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Centennial Olympic Games
closed here Sunday night with the Olympic flag passed to Sydney,
the host city of the 2000 games, amid Australia's traditional
kangaroo dance.
</P>
<P>
The closing ceremony began with the marathon victory ceremony
as Mario V. Rana, a member of the International Olympic Committee,
presented the gold medal to Josia Thugwane of South Africa, winner
of the marathon race held Sunday morning to celebrate the
centennial of its birth.
</P>
<P>
In a tribute to all the athletes who participated in the Games,
local music groups as the Atlanta Symphony Youth Orchestra and the
Morehouse College Glee Club performed rock music, when 3,500
performers, including roller-bladers, skate-boarders and cyclists,
displayed their skills before a packed 83,000-seat stadium.
</P>
<P>
"I declare closed the Games of the 26th Olympiad, the
Centennial Games," said IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch.
"And, in accordance with our tradition, I call upon the youth of
the world to assemble four years from now at Sydney, Australia, to
celebrate with us the Games of the 27th Olympiad, the first Games
of the new Millennium."
</P>
<P>
Samaranch also asked the audience to join together in a moment
of silence to honor the victims of an explosion in the Centennial
Olympic Park that left two dead and 110 injured.
</P>
<P>
"While we celebrate the success of these Games, we have not
forgotten the tragic explosion of last week, nor have we forgotten
the victims," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell returned the 1920 Olympic flag to
Samaranch, who then handed it over to Sydney Mayor Frank Sartor,
before a colorful presentation staged by the Sydney Olympic
Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The presentation, featuring the kangaroo dance, flower girls,
spirit women and cockatoos, gave the world a taste of what is to
be expected four years later in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic flame was extinguished amid the song, "The Flame,"
by American country singer Trisha Yearwood.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony concluded in a gathering of athletes from the 197
countries and regions infield.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
