<HEADLINE> U.S. Heads Medals Table as Olympic Games End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Hosts the United States with 44
gold, 32 silver and 25 bronze medals, leads all teams in the
overall medals table as the 26th Olympic Games end here Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Russia is a distant second with 26 golds, 21 silvers and 14
bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Germany and China maintain their third and fourth position as
in Barcelona four years ago while France has moved up to the 5th
from Barcelona's 9th finisher.
</P>
<P>
With a record 197 IOC members taking part in the Games, the
medals table lists 78 teams, 14 more than in Barcelona and 25 more
than in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Sunday, the last of the 16-day competition, saw Cuba, Ukraine,
Hungary and Germany taking two gold medals each.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's Josia Thugwane beat a star-studded field of 123
to win the gruelling 52.195km men's marathon this morning.
</P>
<P>
Thailand ended its gold drought in the Games when its boxer
Somluck Kamsing took the 57kg class of boxing this afternoon. With
this, Thailand earned two medals from the boxing tournament.
</P>
<P>
Croatia netted its first gold medal when it trounced Sweden
27-25 in the men's handball final.
</P>
<P>
Tonga, a tiny South Pacific island nation, collected its first
ever Olympic medal through boxer Paea Wolfgram who won the silver
in the over-90kg boxing, while Moldova picked up its first silver
in the men's C2 500-meter canaoing sprint event.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands edged out Italy in a closely fought five-set
match to nail the men's volleyball title.
</P>
<P>
In the last final match of the day, the U.S. defeated Brazil
111-87 to clinch the Olympic women's basketball title.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
