<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Centennial Olympic Games End With World Record Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Centennial Olympic Games
concluded here Sunday to be remembered for sporting excellence as
well as the first terror attack since the 1972 Munich Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four world marks tumbled in the 16-day sports gala,
which was marred by undesirable transport and sports results
services and a bomb explosion that left two dead and 110 injured
in the Centennial Olympic Park which was hailed as a symbolism of
peace and unity.
</P>
<P>
Weightlifing was the biggest record smasher with 15 world
marks rewritten. Four world records were broken in swimming, two
in track and field, and one apiece in archery, cycling and
shooting.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Donoran Bailey smashed the men's 100 meters world
record with a time of 9.84 seconds, adding the Olympic title to
his world championship.
</P>
<P>
American sprinter Michael Johnson became the first man to
achieve the 200/400 meters double. He also sliced 0.34 seconds
off his own world record of 19.66 seconds in the 200 meters final.
</P>
<P>
The world sports map has changed in Atlanta as the United
States topped the medals table for the first time in the Olympics
neither boycotted by itself or the former Soviet Union since the
Americans came first overall in the 1964 Tokyo Games.
</P>
<P>
The host country collected 44 gold, 32 silver and 25 bronze
medals. Russia finished second in a 26-21-14 record.
</P>
<P>
No longer as strong as its eastern half in the Seoul Olympics,
nor as a united nation in Barcelona, Germany hang on to its third
spot in the medals standings with an unimpressive 20-18-27
collection.
</P>
<P>
China consolidated its status as the top Asian sports power by
coming fourth overall with 16 golds, 22 silvers and 12 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Wang Junxia took Asia's first women's Olympic distance running
title from the 5,000 meters final, while table tennis player Deng
Yaping and diver Fu Mingxia both hit a gold double.
</P>
<P>
A total of 53 teams struck gold in Atlanta, 16 more than in
Barcelona and 22 more than in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Syria, Hong Kong, Thailand, Ecuador, Burundi, Croatia and Costa
Rica ended their gold droughts in Atlanta, while Kazakhstan,
Belarus, Slovakia and Armenia opened their Olympic gold accounts
in their debut as independent nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overall Medal Tally of Atlanta Olympic Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Following is the overall medal
tally after all the competition at the Centennial Olympic Games
which concluded here on Sunday (tabulated under teams, gold,
silver, bronze and total medals):
</P>
<P>
