<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glory for Olympics, Pride for China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The 495-strong Chinese contingent
have much to hail for and, to some extent, regret as the
Centennial Olympic Games came to a close here Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
The silver-medal performance by their women's volleyballers
Saturday evening virtually wound up the Chinese medal hope for the
16-day competitions.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese were ranked fourth overall here, with a medal haul
of 16 gold, 22 silver and 12 bronze to a medal tally of 50. In
Barcelona, they chalked up a medal credit of 16-22-16 for a total
of 54.
</P>
<P>
Olympic Games judo debutee Sun Fuming won China's first gold
medal at the Games when she overpowered Cuba's silver-medalist
from the Barcelona Games, Estela Rodriguez, in the women's
heavyweight class final.
</P>
<P>
"I had always regarded the gold as being set for me," she said
after the victory.
</P>
<P>
China's "mysterious deer", world champion Wang Junxia, won the
5,000 meters title and made her last effort when surpassed by
Portugese Fernanda Ribeiro 50 meters from the finish line in the
10,000 meters final. But The silver medal she won was praised
anyway by the media on hand.
</P>
<P>
"Wang won over the world with her smile," wrote an news agency
dispatch.
</P>
<P>
Ill-striken veteran shooter Wang Yifu defied a dizzy vision
during men's air pistol final and managed a silver medal on the
Games' opening day. Fainted right after the final shot, the
exhausted 36-year-old was taken as a hero of the Chinese
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese' clean sweep of the table tennis titles once again
proved the depth and strength of the country in the swift sport.
And the victories of the team, trditionally built throught
collective efforts, were at once owed by the coaches and officials
to an all-round, well-schemed preparations.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of fructuated performance by her teammate and
pre-Games favorite Tan Shuping, world and Olympic plaform diving
champion Fu Mingxia made courageous effort in the women's
springboard final. Fu virtually took the gold medal of the event,
making her the first ever Olympic diving champion for both events
at the same Games since 1960.
</P>
<P>
As for the Chinese weight-lifters, unfavored food in the
Olympic Village did foil much of their pre-Games training. But
they managed to take two gold medals, which greatly encouraged the
whole team.
</P>
<P>
Secret for the victories? "Instant noodles," they jokingly
replied.
</P>
<P>
China's male swimmers made a breakthrough at Atlanta Games,
with Jiang Chengji and Zeng Qiliang becoming the country's first
ever finalists in men's events at any Olympic Games. They two
each broke the Asian records of their respective events twice, in
the heats and the final.
</P>
<P>
And the women's volleyballers, the silver-medalists at the
Atlanta Games, were given high appraisal for their recovery from a
disastrous failure in the past years. The team finished seventh
in Barcelona, eighth at the 1994 world championships and third at
last year's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Lang Ping, the former ace striker and captain of the triumphant
Chinese national side during the 1980s, was thought to have played
a key role to pull the team together for what some Chinese media
described as a "rebirth".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Glory for Olympics, Pride for China (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But China's Olympic advance in Atlanta was not all plain
sailing.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swimmers, women in particular, had been tipped
generally as havinng an edge over others in many of the events.
But they bagged only one gold, three silver and two bronze medals,
a poor performance compared to the 4-5-0 record four years ago at
Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
The sole triumph came in the women's 100 meters freestyle,
through the strength of its world champion and world record-holder
Le Jingyi.
</P>
<P>
"This is the most important victory for me as an Olympic gold
is the highest aspiration for any athlete," Le, China's ace
sprinter swimmer said.
</P>
<P>
Both women's butterfly world champion Liu Limin and China's
record-holding 4x100 meters freestyle relay squad failed in their
speciality events.
</P>
<P>
And world's top-ranked Chinese women Chen Yan and Wu Yanyan
even failed to make the final of the women's 400 meters individual
medley.
</P>
<P>
Poor timing of their peak forms for some swimmers, unfavorable
living conditions and mid-night fire alarms at their Olympic
Village dormitory, among others, have been blamed for their
unusually poor physical fitness even before the competitions
started.
</P>
<P>
Badminton is another sport where Chinese were favored to win
medals. But the competitions closed up with China, Indonesia and
Denmark each taking one gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Lack of moral and weak in mental fitness could explain some
Chinese players' under-par performance here. World number one
female player Ye Zhaoying and her male equivalent Dong Jung both
lost their second straight competitions this year, following their
lack-luster performance at the Thomas and Uber Cup events earlier
this year in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With the prime goal of maintaining the fourth overall Olympic
Games ranking reached, officials of the Chinese delegation
expressed satisfaction and relief over their athletes today.
</P>
<P>
"We're happy that China has retained the position it took at
the last Olympic Games and scored progress in some sports and
events," said Yuan Weimin, Deputy Chief de Mission of the Chinese
delegation.
</P>
<P>
"And the breakthrough scored in such influential sports as
swimming, athletics and women's volleyball are especially
encouraging," he said. "It's not just medals that count, it's the
team work and spirit of the athletes," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
