<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands Claim Men's Volleyball Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands defeated Italy
3-2 to take the gold medal of the Olympic men's volleyball
tournament Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands, runners-up in both Olympics and world
championships, played up to their best form to beat the world
champions Italy 15-12, 9-15, 16-14, 9-15 and 17-16.
</P>
<P>
The Italian team, which finished fifth at Barcelona Olympics
four year ago, appeared nervous in the match and could not break
the tight blocking of the Dutch team.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch team, which enjoyed an advantage of height and
strength over their Italian counterparts, had a very good start
and led all the way to take the first set.
</P>
<P>
The Italians played some real good volleyball in the second
set, out-spiking the Dutch team to win in 15-9.
</P>
<P>
But they lost the third set 14-16 to give their rivals a 2-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
Though the Italian again levelled the score at 2-2 after taking
the fourth set 15-9, they were almost exhausted after the long and
fierce competition.
</P>
<P>
The fifth set saw some dramatic changes as the Italian led
14-13 and seemed most likely to take the gold. But the Dutch team
turned the tide and scored three decisive points to win the set
and the match 17-16.
</P>
<P>
In the third place play-off held earlier on Sunday, Yugoslavia
beat Russia 3-1 to take the bronze medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Muslim-Croat Premier Favors Economic ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister of the Bosnian
Muslim-Croat federation Hasan Muratovic said today economic ties
with Yugoslavia should be established first of all in the
industries which used to cooperate in the past.
</P>
<P>
Muratovic told Radio Kragujevac in central Yugoslavia that
joint production should be resumed first, to be followed in a
second stage by a mutual opening of markets.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Muslim-Croat Vice-president Ejup Ganic paid a two-day
visit to Yugoslavia last month and signed a series of agreements
on cooperation in the fields of transportation, communications and
trade.
</P>
<P>
"The federation imports everything across its southern border.
It is aware that Yugoslav food processing industry is particularly
competitive compared to western-made products," Muratovic said,
adding that the federation wished to have access to the port of
Bar in the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the present authorities throughout Bosnia --
both in the federation and in Republika Srpska -- were illegal and
that the forthcoming elections would pave the way for their
legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
The first post-war general elections will be held on September
14 which will vote the Bosnian presidency and leaders of both
entities in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kamsing Takes Thailand's First Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Featherweight boxer Somluck
Kamsing beat Bulgarian world champion Serafim Todorov 8-5 Sunday
to win Thailand's first gold medal.
</P>
<P>
The Thai boxer led from the start and then floated for much of
the third round. The Thai boxer said later he would give his medal
to King Bhumibol Adulyadej who celebrates his 50th anniversary as
Thailand's monarch this year.
</P>
<P>
He led 2-1 after the first round and 5-2 after the second as
the Bulgarian, who beat the U.S. favorite Floyd Mayweather in the
semifinals, was frustrated by the Thai's nimble footwork.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has come close to boxing gold before, their most
recent in 1984 when light-welterweight Dhawee Umponmaha had to
settle for a silver medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
