<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bailey, Johnson Burst into History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- With a bunch of athletic
superstars, the United States won the war of medals, but it is
Canada's Donovan Bailey and American Michael Johnson who rewrote
history through their fabulous feats in the Olympic athletics
competition.
</P>
<P>
After the nine days of thrills and surprises, the U.S.A. team,
which raked up 12 gold medals at the previous Games four years
ago, retained its world No. 1 status by taking 13 titles this
time, chalking up a 13-5-5 total in the 44-event sport.
</P>
<P>
Russia, first competing under its own banner in the Games
history, left way behind with a 3-6-1 collection, ahead of former
track giant Germany, 3-1-3.
</P>
<P>
The athletics competition saw 24 countries claim gold medals
and 45 nations write their names on the medal standing list. It is
the widest ever spread of medals in the Games history. The
previous figures were 18 and 35 respectively in Barcelona four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The most superb performance came from the the men's 200 meters
final, when Johnson, who bid to win an unprecedented double in the
men's 400m and 200m, shocked the world with a rocket-fast new
world record. The 28-year-old talent hit the tape in 19.32
seconds, shedding his own previous world record by 0.34 seconds.
With the 400m gold already in his pocket, Johnson completed his
double victory with a successful period.
</P>
<P>
The world also remebers another magnificent feat produced by
Bailey, Canadan world champion.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old Jamaica-born-Canadian shocked the world like
what his compatriot Ben Johnson did in the 1988 Seoul Games,
incrediblelly improving his personal best to win the men's 100
meters in a world record smashing time of 9.84 seconds. But unlike
"big Ben", Bailey ran the eye-popping race clean, and proved that
his victory at the last year's world championships was not a
fluke.
</P>
<P>
Other superstars who performed brilliantly were Gail Devers of
the United States and Marie-Jose Perec of France. Each won two
golds as Johnson and Bailey did during the Games.
</P>
<P>
Devers, defending Olympic champion, beat Merlene Ottey of
Jamaica again with a photo finish in the women's 100 meters before
taking a 4x100m relay gold. The two had a dead-locked finish at
the 1993 world championships, and it was Devers who was announced
as the 100m winner.
</P>
<P>
Perec, who was mainly a 400m runner but shifted to try the 200
meters here, deprived Ottey of the chance to win the gold in the
half-lap final. The French sprinter, who had won the 400 meters
earlier, beat Ottey by a small margin.
</P>
<P>
Carl Lewis, who had tarnished his name frequently in the past
three years, rose to do big again in the men's long jump, not only
winning his fourth straight Olympic long jump title, but also
becoming the joined fourth athlete who won nine Olympic golds in
history.
</P>
<P>
Also shining in the competition were Noureddine Morceli of
Algeria in the men's 1,500m, Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia in the
men's 5,000m, Jan Zelezny of Czech Republic in the men's javelin,
Lars Riedel of Germany in the men's discus, Wang Junxia of China
in the women's 5,000m, Stefka Kostadinova of Bulgaria in the
women's high jump and Astrid Kumbernuss of Germany in the women's
shot put.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Zelezny, Riedel and Ghada Shouaa of Syria all retained
their Olympic titles successfully.
</P>
<P>
However, the competition also saw some big names suffer
disastrous defeats and the fall of these giants marked an end of
their legendary careers.
</P>
<P>
Jackie Joyner-Kersee of the United States, world record holder
who had dominated the women's heptathon in the past decade, was
hit by an injury again when she started her first multi-event
battle. The 34-year-old had to quit, just like what happened to
her at the previous Games.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Bubka of Ukraine, the world pole vault king who had beat
world records 35 times, also fell victim to an injury in Atlanta,
and had to pull out of the competition in dismay.
</P>
<P>
Ottey, 36, who had 17 Olympic and world championship medals
under her belt before the Games, again failed to gain an Olympic
gold. The eldest sprinter in the Games history wept saddly after
the 100m race, but the never-say-quit Jamaican is the only athlete
who won three medals here - two silvers from 100m and 200m and one
bronze from 4x100m relay.
</P>
<P>
Little-known athletes from small countries celebrated their
victories in many events. Jefferson Perez of Ecuador upset world
stars to win the first Olympic athletics gold in the men's
20-kilometer walk. It is the first Olympic title for Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
Chioma Ajunwa of Nigeria upset world champion and Olympic
champion to win the women's long jump gold, adding another
giant-killing triumph for the third world countries as well as the
first Olympic gold for her country.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's unheralded marathoner Josia Thugwane beat a
world class field to win the last yet most gruelling event in the
athletics - the men's 42.195-kilometer race. It is also the first
Olympic title for his country.
</P>
<P>
Instead of the hot and humid weather, the level of the Olympic
athletics competition reached a new standard and the final results
have proved that the developing countries are catching up with the
traditional world powerhouses at a rapid pace.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960805.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe to Build its Own Global Positioning Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Unhappy with U.S. domination in the
world market of Global Positioning by Satellites System (GPS),
Europe is now planning to build its own version of GPS for aircraft,
ships, vehicles and even persons to decide their exact positions on
earth.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, the European Space Agency (ESA)
decided in late June with the European Commission and the European
Air Navigation Security Organization to launch by 1997 a satellite
navigation system tailered for civilian aviation, shipping and road
transportation.
</P>
<P>
The United States now has 24 "NavStar" satellites orbiting the
earth and making up a GPS that earns two billion U.S. dollars
annually. The NavStars were first built by Garmin, Trimble and
Magellan corporation at the orders of the Pentagon, which wanted to
use the system for "surgical strikes" against enemies.
</P>
<P>
When letting civilians use the GPS, the U.S. military has offered
only its interior technologies insufficient for professional
aviation, in order to avoid a "counter-blow" against U.S. troops by
enemies using the GPS.
</P>
<P>
ESA officials said that Europe does not plan to copy a NavStar,
but wants to improve the performance of such satellites by precising
their positioning capability to 5-10 meters. The project, baptized
"Egnos", is expected to cost 200 million U.S. dollars and enters
service for aircraft, ships and vehicles from 1997, said ESA
officials.
</P>
<P>
At the present world GPS market, a GPS receiver --which is as
small as two cigarette packs-- costs only 400 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although U.S. President Bill Clinton announced in March that
civilians will be allowed to use the military part of GPS in near
future, it will take the U.S. military at least 10 years to build a
permanent system for shutting down GPS in some geographical parts of
the world that are at war, local media observed.
</P>
<P>
An ESA official said that one cannot rule out the possibility
that once a war breaks out, the United States will shut down the
whole GPS system. "The Egnos project is also a mock exam for Europe
to contribute to a world project of GPS," said Alain Pinglier,
coordinator of telecommunication programs of ESA.
</P>
<P>
However, Europe lacks a small satellite launcher to send GPS
satellites into the orbit, as the Ariane rocket caters only for big
satellites. This problem casts a shadow over the "Egnos", which is
described by local media as a gamble of Europe to enter the
lucrative and newly developing GPS market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
